This field contains the combined results of 2 ACE touchscreen questions, both asked "Has/did your ADOPTED mother ever suffer from? (You can select more than one answer)" for different sets of illnesses. For convenience, the illnesses were arbitrarily divided into two sets:

  • Group 1 : Heart disease, Stroke, High blood pressure, Chronic bronchitis/emphysema, Alzheimer's disease/dementia, Diabetes.
  • Group 2 : Parkinson's disease, Severe Depression, Lung cancer, Bowel cancer, Breast cancer.

If any of codes -11, -13 or -17 were selected then no additional Group 1 choices were allowed. If any of codes -21, -23 or -27 were selected then no additional Group 2 choices were allowed.

If the participant activated the Help button they were shown the message:
Answer this question for your adopted mother only. If you are not sure if your adopted mother suffered from any of the listed illnesses please select Do not know. If you know your adopted mother suffered from certain listed illnesses but are unsure about others, only select the ones you are sure about.

The information was collected from participants who indicated they were adopted as a child, as defined by their answers to ~F1767~ and who indicated whether their adopted mother was still alive or had died, as defined by their answers to ~F3942~.

Note that although Prostate cancer is present in ~C1010~, participants were not presented with this option when selecting adopted Mother illnesses.

title: Illnesses of adopted siblings
notes:
This field contains the combined results of 2 ACE touchscreen questions, both asked "Have any of your ADOPTED brothers or sisters suffered from any of the following diseases? (You can select more than one answer)" for different sets of illnesses. For convenience, the illnesses were arbitrarily divided into two sets:

  • Group 1 : Heart disease, Stroke, High blood pressure, Chronic bronchitis/emphysema, Alzheimer's disease/dementia, Diabetes.
  • Group 2 : Parkinson's disease, Severe Depression, Lung cancer, Bowel cancer, Prostate cancer, Breast cancer.

If any of codes -11, -13 or -17 were selected then no additional Group 1 choices were allowed. If any of codes -21, -23 or -27 were selected then no additional Group 2 choices were allowed.

If the participant activated the Help button they were shown the message:
Answer this question for adopted brothers and sisters only. Include any adopted sisters or brothers who have died. If you are not sure if your adopted sisters or brothers suffered from any of the listed illnesses please select Do not know. If more than one adopted sister or brother has suffered from any of the listed illnesses, you only need to select the illness once.

The information was collected from participants who indicated they were adopted as a child, as defined by their answers to ~F1767~ and that they had at least one adopted brother or sister, as defined by their answers to ~F3972~ and ~F3982~.

title: Country of Birth (non-UK origin)
notes:
This is the country of birth as described by the participant to an interviewer. The question was only asked to participants who identified themselves as having been born outside of the United Kingdom / Republic of Ireland during the touchscreen questionnaire (~F1647~), however some participants then gave a location within the United Kingdom / Republic of Ireland (and have been coded here as such).

Answers have been grouped by continent. Coding was performed after the assessment visit using the strings either selected or entered as free-text. Some of the free-text could not be mapped onto a region and these entries have been omitted from the dataset.

In some cases participants declared an occupation which was not actually classified as paid/self-employment and this information was used to correct the answer given in ~F6142~.

title: Neuroticism score
notes:
This is an externally derived summary score of neuroticism, based on 12 neurotic behaviour domains as reported from fields 1920, 1930, 1940, 1950, 1960, 1970, 1980, 1990, 2000, 2010, 2020 and 2030 from the touchscreen questionnaire at baseline. Participants were assessed for twelve domains of neurotic behaviours via the touchscreen questionnaire. Questions included:
  • Does your mood often go up and down?
  • Do you ever feel 'just miserable' for no reason?
  • Are you an irritable person?
  • Are your feelings easily hurt?
  • Do you often feel 'fed-up'?
  • Would you call yourself a nervous person?
  • Are you a worrier?
  • Would you call yourself tense or 'highly strung'?
  • Do you worry too long after an embarrassing experience?
  • Do you suffer from 'nerves'?
  • Do you often feel lonely?
  • Are you often troubled by feelings of guilt?
Participants could answer Yes, No, Do not know or Prefer not to answer.

This field summarises the number of Yes answers across these twelve questions into a single integer score for each participant.

This derived data field has come from Professor Jill Pell from the Institute of Health & Wellbeing, University of Glasgow. Methods on how these fields were derived can be found in the Additional Resources tab.

notes:
Highest measure from the array of values for Forced Expiratory Volume in 1-second (FEV1) ~F3063~, which was "acceptable" according to corresponding acceptability field (~F3061~). A blow was deemed acceptable if recorded as 0 (no problems) or 32 (0x20 - "USER_ACCEPTED").

This derived data field has come from Professor Martin Tobin at the University of Leicester.

title: Forced vital capacity (FVC), Best measure
notes:
Highest measure from the array of values for Forced Vital Capacity (FVC) (~F3062~), which was "acceptable" according to corresponding acceptability field (~F3061~). A blow was deemed acceptable if recorded as 0 (no problems) or 32 (0x20 - "USER_ACCEPTED").

This derived data field has come from Professor Martin Tobin at the University of Leicester.

title: Reproduciblity of spirometry measurement using ERS/ATS criteria
notes:
Indicates whether an individual's spirometry meets European Respiratory Society/American Thoracic Society (ERS/ATS) Criteria, that is their highest acceptable measure was reproducible (the highest acceptable measure and any other measure were within 150 millilitres for both for Forced Expiratory Volume in 1-second (FEV1) and Forced Vital Capacity (FVC), although not necessarily the same blow. Note, if FVC <=1 litre the criteria is within 100 millilitres).

This derived data field has come from Professor Martin Tobin at the University of Leicester.

title: Forced expiratory volume in 1-second (FEV1), predicted
notes:
Predicted Forced Expiratory Volume in 1-second (FEV1), was calculated using a subset of "healthy never smokers" from UK Biobank. "Healthy never smokers", were selected as individuals with "Ever Smoking Status"=0 and with "Reproducible measure using the European Respiratory Society/American Thoracic Society (ERS/ATS) Criteria"=YES (1), with the following exclusions:
  • ~F2316~: Individuals who indicated that they had experienced wheeze: "Yes" (1), "Do not know" (-1) or "Prefer not to answer" (-3).
  • ~F6152~: Individuals who reported "emphysema/chronic bronchitis" (6) or "asthma" (8) or "Prefer not to answer" (-3).
  • ~F20002~: Individuals who reported any of the following: asthma (1111), COPD (1112), emphysema/chronic bronchitis (1113), bronchiectasis (1114), interstitial lung disease (1115), asbestosis (1120), pulmonary fibrosis (1121), fibrosing/unspecified alveolitis (1122), respiratory failure (1124), pleurisy (1125), spontaneous/recurrent pneumothorax (1126), other respiratory problems (1117).
Healthy never smokers were grouped into 58 age-sex bands (29 age bands per sex; ages 39, 40 and 41 were grouped into one band and ages 69, 70 and 72 were grouped into one band with ages 42 to 68 each forming a separate band) and the following linear regression model was fitted in each age-sex band:

FEV1 = Beta0 + Beta1 * Standing Height

Predicted FEV1 was then calculated for all samples who were never smokers ("Ever Smoking Status"=0) or heavy smokers ("Ever Smoking Status"=1 AND "Pack years as proportion of life span exposed to smoking" >= 0.42) and with "Reproducible measure using the European Respiratory Society/American Thoracic Society (ERS/ATS) Criteria"=YES, using the estimates of Beta0 and Beta1, from the appropriate age-sex band:

Predicted FEV1= (pred.Beta0) + (pred.Beta1)^ * Standing Height

Five individuals were outliers in terms of their FEV1 and were not coded.

This derived data field has come from Professor Martin Tobin at the University of Leicester.

The current field was updated in 2021, using the regression method described above. Coverage was increased to include any participant who indicated at initial assessment (instance 0) that they either occasionally smoked, or where "Pack years as proportion of life span exposed to smoking" < 0.42.

The original research group additionally indicated that they now use GLI-2012 equations to produce predicted values for FEV1, details can be found at ~Ehttps://www.ers-education.org/guidelines/global-lung-function-initiative/faq/how-to-use-the-quanjer-gli-2012-equations.aspx~.

title: Forced expiratory volume in 1-second (FEV1), predicted percentage
notes:
This value was only calculated for samples with non-missing predicted Forced Expiratory Volume in 1-second, using derived variables Force Expiratory Volume in 1-second (FEV1) and predicted Forced Expiratory Volume in 1-second (pred.FEV1). It is defined as the Force Expiratory Volume in 1-second divided by the Percent predicted Forced Expiratory Volume in 1-second multiplied by 100:

FEV1 /pred.FEV1 * 100

This derived data field has come from Professor Martin Tobin at the University of Leicester.

title: Number of symbol digit matches made correctly
notes: This is the number of times a participant correctly matched a symbol with a digit summed across all the rounds of the test that they performed, excluding the initial 8 items corresponding to the training round.

title: Ever smoked
notes:
Derived using variables "Current tobacco smoking" (~F1239~) and "Past tobacco smoking" (~F1249~).

Individual classed as Eversmoker if Current tobacco smoking= most days (1) or occasionally (2) OR Past tobacco smoking= most days (1) or occasionally (2) or tried once or twice (3).

Individual were classed as Neversmoker if Current tobacco smoking= no (0) AND Past tobacco smoking= never (4).

Individuals who answered to either question "Do not know" (-1) "Prefer not to answer" (-3) and "None of the above" (-7) were not coded.

This derived data field has come from Professor Martin Tobin at the University of Leicester.

title: Pack years of smoking
notes:
Pack years calculated for individuals who have ever smoked according to data field Ever smoking status=1, using appropriate data: Current cigarette (either manufactured or hand rolled) smokers who smoke most days (smoking data fields used: ~F3436~ and ~F6183~). Past cigarette (either manufactured or hand rolled) smokers who smoked most days (smoking data fields used: ~F2867~, ~F2897~ and ~F2887~). Current cigar/pipe smokers who smoked most days and previously smoked cigarettes (smoking data fields used: ~F3436~, ~F6194~ and ~F6183~). The general definition of a pack year is the number of cigarettes smoked per day, divided by twenty, multiplied by the number of years of smoking. The number of years of smoking is calculated by substracting the age of starting smoking from the age smoking was stopped.

Number of cigarettes per day / 20 * (Age stopped smoking - Age start smoking)

The figure is adjusted for individuals who gave up smoking for more than 6 months, according to data fields 2907 or 3486 by subtracting six months from the number of years of smoking.

Number of cigarettes per day / 20 * (Age stopped smoking - Age start smoking - 0.5)

Note: Individuals who started and gave up smoking before 16 years of age were coded as NA. For individuals who started smoking before 16 but gave up after 16, their age start was set as 16. Individuals who reported starting and stopping smoking at the same age and reported giving up smoking for more than 6 months had pack-years set at 0.

This derived data field has come from Professor Martin Tobin at the University of Leicester.

title: Pack years adult smoking as proportion of life span exposed to smoking
notes:
Average number of pack-years smoked by an individual each year, over their adult lifetime, calculated using pack-years data field. Pack years as a proportion of lifespan exposed to smoking is defined as pack years divided by the number of years between the participants' age at recruitment and the age of 16:

Pack years / (Age at recruitment - 16)

This derived data field has come from Professor Martin Tobin at the University of Leicester.

title: First code array presented
notes:
The tests were described by an outer array of 33 symbol-digit arrays each containing the digits 0-7. To present some element of unpredictability between participants, each run of the program chose a random starting point in the outer array and presented tests from that point onwards (looping back to the origin if required). The outer array was zero-indexed, so that a value of 0 in this field means that the first symbol-digit array was used for the Coding array.

To illustrate, suppose a participant was allocated the value 5 for their start array. Then round 1 would use Array 5 [values 3,5,2,0,4,6,1,7] for the Code and Array 6 [6,3,7,2,4,5,0,1] for the Test. Round 2 would still use Array 5 for the Code but Array 7 [1,4,5,6,0,7,2,3] for the test etc.

title: Values wanted
notes:
This is the value matching the displayed symbol according to the coding dictionary presented on the screen.

To illustrate, the initial training screen displays

  • [2,4,6,1,3,5,7,0] - code (upper) Array
  • [7,1,5,4,6,0,3,2] - test (lower) Array
Then the leftmost picture in the test Array has value 7 (a crescent). In the upper code array the crescent appears above the numeral 7, so the value wanted here is 7.

The next item in the test Array has value 1 ("H" shape), which appears above the numeral 4 in the code array.

The last item in the test Array has value 2 ("=" symbol), which appears above the numeral 1 in the code array.

title: T1 structural brain images - DICOM
notes:
The DICOM image was acquired using the following parameters:

Resolution: 1x1x1 mm
Field-of-view: 208x256x256 matrix
Scan duration: 5 minutes
3D MPRAGE, sagittal, in-plane acceleration iPAT=2, prescan-normalise

title: Functional brain images - task - DICOM
notes:
The DICOM images were acquired using the following parameters:

Resolution: 2.4x2.4x2.4 mm
Field-of-view: 88x88x64 matrix
Duration: 4 minutes (332 timepoints)
TR: 0.735 s
TE: 39ms
GE-EPI with x8 multislice acceleration, no iPAT, flip angle 52 degrees, fat saturation

As implemented in the CMRR multiband acquisition, a separate "single-band reference scan" is also acquired. This has the same geometry (including EPI distortion) as the timeseries data, but has higher between-tissue contrast to noise, and is used as the reference scan in head motion correction and alignment to other modalities.

title: Multiband diffusion brain images - DICOM
notes:
The DICOM images were acquired using the following parameters:

Resolution: 2x2x2 mm
Field-of-view: 104x104x72 matrix
Duration: 7 minutes (including 36 seconds phase-encoding reversed data)
10x b=0, 50x b=1000, 50x b=2000
SE-EPI with x3 multislice acceleration, no iPAT, fat saturation

For the two diffusion-weighted shells, 50 distinct diffusion-encoding directions were acquired (and all 100 directions are distinct). The diffusion prepraration is a standard ("monopolar") Stejskal-Tanner pulse sequence. This enables higher SNR due to a shorter echo time (TE=92ms) than than a twice-refocused ("bipolar") sequence. This improvement comes at the expense of stronger eddy current distortions, which are removed in the processed data available in NIFTI format.

title: Susceptibility weighted brain images - DICOM
notes:
The DICOM images were acquired using the following parameters:

Resolution: 0.8x0.8x3 mm
Field-of-view: 256x288x48 matrix
Duration: 2.5 minutes
Two echos, TE=9.42,20 ms
2D, axial, in-plane acceleration iPAT=2, partial Fourier = 7/8, prescan-normalise

To date (Oct 2015) the magnitude and phase images have been saved for each RF coil and echo time separately. In future the expectation is to combine these on the scanner

title: T2 FLAIR structural brain images - DICOM
notes:
The DICOM images were acquired using the following parameters:

Resolution: 1.05x1x1 mm
Field-of-view: 192x256x256 matrix
Duration: 6 minutes
3D SPACE, sagittal, in-plane acceleration iPAT=2, partial Fourier = 7/8, fat saturation, elliptical k-space scanning, prescannormalise

title: T2/PD brain images - DICOM
notes: The T2/PD scan was originally tentatively included as a standard protocol in diagnostic imaging for the detection of some pathologies. Consultation with research experts concluded it has little or no value to the research questions UK Biobank is likely to investigate. Further, the b=0 dMRI scans can to some extent be used as a surrogate for this. Hence in the face of overall scan time pressure, the T2/PD scan was dropped from the protocol during the pilot.

title: Home location at assessment - Output Area (2001 census, old code format)
notes:
This field contains 2001 Census output areas corresponding to each participant's home address at assessment, in the original coding format.

These codes were later replaced by standardised 9-character codes in the format used across ONS geographies (published in ~F20270~). Census output areas are built from clusters of adjacent unit postcodes and were designed to have similar population sizes and be as socially homogenous as possible. Output areas in Scotland are smaller than in England and Wales.

Output Area fields will only be released following special approval. If access is approved, researchers will be required to hold these data-fields separately from their main project (a new set of encoded ids will be supplied) while they derive their required measures, which will then be made available to their main project only after these fields have been deleted.

For most purposes, higher aggregations of census/administrative areas will provide sufficient information on location of residence at assessment. These rounded values are found in ~F20271~ and ~F20272~.

This field will only be released following special approval.

For most purposes, these areas will provide sufficient information on location of residence at assessment. If a higher level of granularity is required, codes are also available for Output Areas, which can be found in ~F20270~.

This field will only be released following special approval.

For most purposes, these areas will provide sufficient information on location of residence at assessment. If a higher level of granularity is required, codes are also available for LSOAs, which can be found in ~F20271~.

Question asked: "Please think of the period in your life when you have felt worried, tense, anxious, or more worried than most people would in your situation. title: When food preferences questionnaire completed
notes: When food preferences questionnaire was completed by participant.

title: Duration of questionnaire
notes:
The time participants took to complete the food preferences questionnaire are measured from first starting it to clicking the sign-off button on the final screen. Participants were able to complete the questionnaire over multiple sessions so a long time need not indicate they were continuously connected.

Times are rounded down to the nearest minute.

title: Number of puzzles correctly solved
notes: This is the number of puzzles for which the participant gave the correct solution. It should be used in conjunction with ~F20761~ which describes the number of puzzles attempted. The range is 0-15.

title: Number of puzzles viewed
notes:
This is the number of puzzles which the participant viewed irrespective of whether they supplied any answer (though the were unable to progress to the next puzzle without supplying an answer). The range is 0-15.

If the participant did not attempt all 15 puzzles then this value is likely to be greater than the number of entries for ~20762~ and~20763~ as it will usually include a last puzzle which was viewed by the participant but for which an answer was not selected within the overall time limit.

title: Item selected for each puzzle
notes:
This indicates the item selected for each puzzle as illustrated in ~R15~.
For puzzles which had 6 options the codes 0-5 correspond to the following layout:

0 1 2
3 4 5

For puzzles which had 8 options the codes 0-7 correspond to the following layout:

0 1 2 3
4 5 6 7

If a participant answered all 15 puzzles correctly the sequence would be: 3,2,5,0,3,5,0,5,3,0,7,1,4,2,6

title: Duration spent answering each puzzle
notes:
This is an array of values, one for each puzzle answered, detailing how long the participant spent looking at a puzzle before selecting their answer.

Some values are zero indicating a response time of less than 0.1 seconds, which is below the realistic minimum time for mentally processing the picture and deciding which image to touch. Such values are assumed to be due to a participant hovering a finger over the screen and accidentally making contact with it when the puzzle first appears.

title: Matrices puzzle completion status
notes: Matrix pattern completion status

title: When matrices puzzle completed
notes: When matrices puzzle completed

title: Ethnic background
notes:
This is an amalgam of sequential branching questions asked during the initial Assessment Centre visit as part of the touchscreen questionnaire.

The question was dropped from the touchscreen protocol on 24/10/2016. It was reintroduced in early 2023, as it was required as a parameter for some repeat imaging measures.

title: Body mass index (BMI)
notes: BMI value here is constructed from height and weight measured during the initial Assessment Centre visit. Value is not present if either of these readings were omitted.

title: Weight
notes: Weight was measured by a variety of means during the initial Assessment Centre visit. This field amalgamates these values into a single item.

title: Age when attended assessment centre
notes: This is a derived variable based on date of birth and date of attending assessment centre and refers to the age of the participant on the day they attended an Assessment Centre, truncated to whole year part.

title: Number of puzzles correct
notes: Number of puzzles correct, scored from the participant answers in ~F6312~.

title: L1-L4 TBS (trabecular bone score)
notes: Trabecular bone scores derived by ~N17295~. Please note for a very small percentage of participants the TBS value for certain lumbar vertebrae are missing and the mean TBS score has been calculated using the remaining lumbar vertebrae. Please see ~D4322~ for the source of the data which includes a file indicating which lumbar vertebrae have been included in the mean value for each participant.

title: Imputation from genotype (TOPmed)
notes:
Imputation from genotype using the TOPMed R2 panel, performed by the TOPMed Informatics Research Center. Primary description of the imputation data can be found in: Taliun, D., Harris, D.N., Kessler, M.D. et al. Sequencing of 53,831 diverse genomes from the NHLBI TOPMed Program. Nature 590, 290-299 (2021) ~Ehttps://doi.org/10.1038/s41586-021-03205-y~

After phasing the UK Biobank genetic data (carried out on 81 chromosomal chunks using Eagle v.2.4), the phased data were converted from GRCh37 to GRCh38 using LiftOver. Imputation was performed using Minimac4 v1.0.2 (~Ehttps://genome.sph.umich.edu/wiki/Minimac4~). The reference panel is the TOPMed R2 panel, which is available to public at ~Ehttps://imputation.biodatacatalyst.nhlbi.nih.gov~. Imputation was performed in 1Mb chunks and merged back together by chromosome. Due to large data size, markers with poor imputation were not retained (excluded Minimac4 imputation quality metric R^2 < 0.1). Across all the chromosomes, 677,037 markers were used for imputation.
For distribution to UK Biobank, output Minimac4 VCF files were converted to BGEN format using qctool v2.0.8. The conversion used the Genotype Probability (GP) field from source VCF and the probabilities are stored using 8 bit precision.

Details on contributing cohorts for the TOPMed Imputataion Panel can be seen in Extended Table 3 of Sequencing of 53,831 diverse genomes from the NHLBI TOPMed Program. Nature 590, 290-299 (2021). ~Ehttps://doi.org/10.1038/s41586-021-03205-y~.

title: Imputation from genotype (Genomics England)
notes: Imputation from genotype lifted over from GRCh37 to GRCh38, performed by Genomics England using a high coverage (30x) sequencing dataset from the Genomics England (GEL) 100,000 genomes project.

title: FDA data file (left)
notes: The fda file contains the compressed fundus image and 3D OCT scan data together with the results of the analysis done by the OCT device for the left eye. File size is typically 5 MB.

title: FDS data file (left)
notes: The fds file contains the raw fundus image and 3D OCT scan data for the left eye. File size is typically 97 MB.

title: FDA data file (right)
notes: The fda file contains the compressed fundus image and 3D OCT scan data together with the results of the analysis done by the OCT device for the right eye. File size is typically 5 MB.

title: FDS data file (right)
notes: The fds file contains the raw fundus image and 3D OCT scan data for the right eye. File size is typically 97 MB.

title: Fundus retinal eye image (left)
notes: The fundus image of the retina of the left eye. Images are stored in PNG-format, approximately 2MB each.

title: Fundus retinal eye image (right)
notes: The fundus image of the retina of the right eye. Images are stored in PNG-format, approximately 2MB each.

title: OCT image slices (left)
notes: Individual images of OCT slices through left retina in PNG format.

title: OCT image slices (right)
notes: Individual images of OCT slices through right retina in PNG format.

title: Pulse wave Arterial Stiffness index
notes: The time between peaks of the waveform (the peak-to-peak time) is divided into the persons height to obtain the Stiffness Index.  This value was calculated outside the Assessment Centre visit as the participant height was not known until after the stiffness device had been used.

title: Severity of current abdominal pain
notes:
Question asked: "How severe is your abdominal pain?"

Participants were asked to move the slider to choose a number from 0 to 10, with 0 meaning "no pain" and 10 meaning "very severe". Participants using an older browser were asked to select a button from 0 to 10.

Question asked if ~F21035~ was "Yes".

title: Number of days (out of 10) with abdominal pain
notes:
Question asked: "Please move the slider to select the number of times that you get the pain every 10 days. For example, if you choose 4 it means that you get pain 4 out of 10 days. If you get pain every day enter 10."

Participants using an older browser were asked to select a button from 0 to 10.

Question asked if ~F21035~ was "Yes".

title: Currently suffer from abdominal distension
notes: Question asked: "Do you currently suffer from abdominal distension? (bloating, swollen or tight tummy) Women please ignore distension related to your period."

title: Severity of current abdominal distension/tightness
notes:
Question asked: "How severe is your abdominal distension/tightness?"

Participants were asked to move a slider to choose a number from 0 to 10, with 0 meaning "no distension" and 10 meaning "very severe". Participants using an older browser were asked to select a button from 0 to 10.

title: Satisfaction with bowel habits
notes:
Question asked: "How happy/satisfied are you with your bowel habits?"

Participants were asked to move a slider to choose a number from 0 to 10, with 0 meaning "very happy" and 10 meaning "very unhappy". Participants using an older browser were asked to select a button from 0 to 10.

title: Degree to which abdominal pain/discomfort/altered bowel habits affect/interfere with life in general
notes:
Question asked: "Please indicate how much abdominal pain or discomfort or altered bowel habits are affecting or interfering with your life in general."

Participants were asked to move a slider to choose a number between 0 to 10, with 0 meaning "not at all" and 10 meaning "completely". Participants using an older browser were asked to select a button from 0 to 10.

title: Greatest number of times bowels opened per day
notes:

Values entered here were restricted to the range 1 to 40.

title: Least number of times bowels opened per week

title: Number of weeks absent from work due to IBS, in the last year
notes:
Question asked: "In the last year approximately how many weeks were you absent from work due to IBS?"

Participants were asked to answer 0 if they had IBS but it did not prevent them from going to work.

title: When gave up work due to IBS
notes:
Question asked when the participant had given up work due to IBS.

The reported month and year have been converted into a date with the date in the month given as the 1st. For participants who provided the year only (i.e. without a month) a value of 1st July was used.

Question asked if ~F21024~ was "Yes" and ~F21045~ was "Given up work because of IBS".

title: Number of weeks (in the last year) at work suffering because of IBS
notes:
Question asked how many weeks (in the last year) the participant was at work suffering because of IBS.

  • Participants where instructed to enter 0 if IBS did not affect them at work in the last year
  • Participants were instructed to enter 52 if IBS affects them at work all the time.
Question asked if ~F21024~ was "Yes" and ~F21045~ was neither "Given up work because of IBS" nor "Do not work".

title: Genotype measurement batch
notes:
Genotyping was done using two closely related arrays, referred to as the UK BiLEVE array and the UK Biobank Axiom array. The BiLEVE array was designed first and run on ~50,000 participants. The UKB Axiom array was designed subsequently with a view to maximizing marker overlap as much as possible between the arrays and run on the remaining ~450,000 participants. The UKB Axiom array had over 820,000 SNPs and indel markers, and the UK BiLEVE array was very similar with over 95% common content.

Samples were analysed in batches of approximately 4700 items. Interim results from first 33 batches (UKBiLEVE_b1-11 and Batch_b001-022) were released 18 months ahead of the remainder. The CEL files from these interim batches were subsequently re-analysed as part of the QC process for the full release, and this resulted in minor changes to the associated calls.

title: Genetic sex
notes:
Sex as determined from genotyping analysis.

In a small number (38) of cases the genetic sex currently listed differs from that calculated at the earlier 'Interim 150K' release. The new values are the result of re-genotyping these samples as they were felt to be of insufficient quality, and the genetic sex now agrees with the sex provided in ~F31~ that was sourced from central registry at recruitment but was updated if the participant reported it was incorrect.

Note that in over 300 cases the genetic sex differs from the self-reported value in ~F31~.

title: CEL files
notes:
CEL files

Files are downloaded using the ukbfetch utility as described in ~R644~.

title: Heterozygosity
notes: Heterozygosity across a set of high-quality markers. See genotype QC documentation (~R530~) for details.

title: Heterozygosity, PCA corrected
notes: Heterozygosity after adjusting for ancestry using principal components. This metric was used to identify outliers based on heterozygosity and missing rates. See genotype QC documentation (~R530~) for details.

title: Missingness
notes: Missing rate of each sample based on a set of high-quality markers.

title: Genetic ethnic grouping
notes:
Genetic ethnic group.

Indicates samples who self-identified as 'White British' according to ~F21000~ and have very similar genetic ancestry based on a principal components analysis of the genotypes.

title: Genotype measurement plate
notes: This field indicates on which 96-well plate a particular sample was measured.

title: Genotype measurement well
notes: Genotype measurements were conducted using 96-well plates. This field indicates the position within a plate of the well used to contain a particular participants sample.

title: Genetic principal components
notes: Score for each principal component 1-40. See genotype QC documentation in ~R530~ for details.

title: Recommended genomic analysis exclusions
notes: During processing of the genotype data it was deemed that certain samples showed signs of insufficient data quality, and it is recommend their genotype data should not be included in analyses such as GWAS. This field identifies these samples and the reason(s) for recommending their exclusion. Details of the analysis used to detect these samples will be given in forthcoming documentation.

title: Genetic relatedness pairing
notes:
This field is used to identify pairs of participants who are estimated to be genetically related.

Because each set of data distributed to researchers is anonymised differently it is impractical to provide an individually customised list of related participants IDs. Instead, each pairing of related participants is assigned a unique number, and the pairings can be reconstructed by identifying participants who share the same number.

The strength of the inferred relationship is indicated in ~F22012~ and ~F22013~.

title: Genetic relatedness factor
notes: This field gives the kinship coefficient associated with each pair of participants who have the same value for the Genetic relatedness pairing in ~F22011~.

title: Genetic relatedness IBS0
notes:
This field gives the IBS0 value associated with each pair of participants who have the same value for the Genetic relatedness pairing in ~F22011~.

For a pair of genotypes, IBS0 it is the proportion of SNPs where one sample carries two A alleles, and the other carries two B alleles.

title: Average X chromosome intensities for determining sex
notes: Average intensities for variants on the X chromosome used for determining genetic sex.

title: Average Y chromosome intensities for determining sex
notes: Average intensities for variants on the Y chromosome used for determining genetic sex.

title: Invitation to complete online occupational questionnaire, date sent
notes: Dates that invitations to online occupational health questionnaire were emailed to participants.

title: When invitation to complete online cognitive function questionnaire sent
notes: Dates that invitations to online cognitive function questionnaire were emailed to participants.

title: Genetic relatedness exclusions
notes: This field identifies the persons excluded from the calculations of genetic relatedness and gives the reasons for their exclusion.

title: Sex chromosome aneuploidy
notes: Sex chromosome aneuploidy marker. This indicates samples which were identified as putatively carrying sex chromosome configurations that are not either XX or XY. These were identified by looking at average log2Ratios for Y and X chromosomes.

title: Used in genetic principal components
notes: Indicates participants whose samples were used to compute the genetic principal components in ~F22009~. All samples with genotype data were subsequently projected onto each of the 40 computed components.

title: Genetic kinship to other participants
notes: Genetic kinship to other participants

title: Sex inference X probe-intensity
notes: Affymetrix metric used for determining sex. Measures average probe intensity on a set of non-polymorphic probes on the X chromosome. Note this set of probes are not in the genotype calls.

title: Sex inference Y probe-intensity
notes: Affymetrix metric used for determining sex. Measures average probe intensity on a set of non-polymorphic probes on the Y chromosome. Note this set of probes are not in the genotype calls.

title: DNA concentration
notes: Measure of DNA concentration in sample used by Affymetrix to determine genotypes. Labelled in dataset as Internal.Pico..ng.uL.

title: Affymetrix quality control metric "Cluster.CR"
notes: Affymetrix quality control metric. Corresponds to sample-specific call rate for each individual, computed using probesets internal to Affymetrix.

title: Affymetrix quality control metric "dQC"
notes: Affymetrix quality control metric. Measures the resolution of the distributions of intensity 'contrast' values, based on intensities of probe sequences for non-polymorphic genome locations. See Affymetrix SNP-polisher documentation for details. Note that values were rounded to 2 decimal places for individuals type on the UKBiobank array, and 5 decimal places for individuals typed on the UKBiLEVE array.

title: Outliers for heterozygosity or missing rate
notes: Indicates samples identified as outliers in heterozygosity and missing rates, which implies that the genotypes for these samples are of poor quality.

title: Use in phasing Chromosomes 1-22
notes: Indicates whether data from a participant was used in phasing calculation for Chromosomes 1-22.

title: Use in phasing Chromosome X
notes: Indicates whether data from a participant was used in phasing calculation for Chromosome X.

title: Use in phasing Chromosome XY
notes: Indicates whether data from a participant was used in phasing calculation for Chromosome XY.

title: UKBiLEVE Affymetrix quality control for samples
notes:
Sample quality control undertaked by Affymetrix was a DNA quality filter (dish quality control < 0.82) and initial clustering call rate (<97%). 520 duplicates passed Affymetrix quality control in both samples, 33 passed Affymetrix quality control in 1 sample, 0 duplicates failed Affymetrix quality control in both samples. Therefore keeping 1 of each duplicate (the 1 that passed) 50,008 unique samples were present.

This derived data field has come from Professor Martin Tobin at the University of Leicester.

title: UKBiLEVE genotype quality control for samples
notes:
Quality control steps carried out in Leicester (the location of the UKBiLEVE project) were:
  • sex mismatch (remove sample if submitted gender is different to gender inferred from sex chromosomes);
  • final call rate (<95%), heterozygosity outliers (outlier if > 3sd from mean heterozygosity);
  • unintended duplicate (> 98% of alleles shared identical by descent);
  • ancestry principal components outlier (outlier if >10sd from mean on first 10 principal components).

This derived data field has come from Professor Martin Tobin at the University of Leicester.

title: UKBiLEVE unrelatedness indicator
notes:
Indicates whether a UKBiLEVE sample may be included in a subset of unrelated UKBiLEVE samples. Samples were coded as "Not_tested" if they failed Affymetrix quality control (~F22050~) or Leicester quality control (~F22051~).

~F22011~ should be used if the set of participants being analysed included non-UKBiLEVE samples.

This derived data field has come from Professor Martin Tobin at the University of Leicester.

title: HLA imputation values
notes:
Each entry contains all HLA loci (one line per person) in the following order:

A, B, C, DRB5, DRB4, DRB3, DRB1, DQB1, DQA1, DPB1, DPA1

There is one value (separated by commas) per imputed allele and only the best-guess alleles are reported. The quantities P(A1|D) and P(A2|D,A1) from the Q column of the HLA:IMP*2 output are reported for each locus. For further information on the calculation methodology and the Quality metric see ~R182~.

To download an example row of data see ~R1520~.

title: Townsend deprivation index at recruitment
notes:
Townsend deprivation index calculated immediately prior to participant joining UK Biobank. Based on the preceding national census output areas. Each participant is assigned a score corresponding to the output area in which their postcode is located.

The values here are rounded to 2 decimal places, replacing an earlier unrounded version.

title: Unadjusted T/S ratio
notes:
Relative leucocyte telomere length measured by quantitative PCR. This measure is a ratio of telomere repeat copy number to single copy gene (HBB) copy number, relative to a standard sample. Full details of the methodology used to measure telomere length can be found in Codd, V. et al (~Ehttps://doi.org/10.1101/2021.03.18.21253457~.)

Please note that this is a raw measure and has not been adjusted to remove technical variation. We strongly recommend that for any analysis, researchers use the technically adjusted measures provided in ~F22191~ (Adjusted T/S ratio) or ~F22192~ (Z-adjusted T/S). Details of the technical adjustment can also be found in Codd, V. et al (~Ehttps://doi.org/10.1101/2021.03.18.21253457~.)

title: Adjusted T/S ratio
notes: Relative leucocyte telomere length (~F22190~) adjusted for the influence of technical parameters. Full details of the technical adjustment can be found in Codd, V. et al (~Ehttps://doi.org/10.1101/2021.03.18.21253457~).

title: Z-adjusted T/S log
notes: Technically adjusted leucocyte telomere length (~F22191~) which has been both loge-transformed to obtain a normal distribution and then Z-standardised using the distribution of all individuals with a telomere length measurement. We recommend the use of these measurements to allow comparison to other studies where Z-standardised measures are available Full details of these measures and adjustments can be found in Codd, V. et al (~Ehttps://doi.org/10.1101/2021.03.18.21253457~), and exemplar use of the measurements, including a GWAS, can be found in Codd, V. et al (~Ehttps://doi.org/10.1101/2021.03.23.21253516~.)

title: Telomere measurement plate
notes: Original telomere measurement plate. Note that most samples were replated from the shipping plate for measurement, so this is an unreliable indicator of group/batch effects and thus will not be routinely distributed.

title: T/S ratio for regression dilution bias
notes:
To gain an estimate of within-individual variation in leucocyte telomere length, paired measurements were made for 1351 UK Biobank participants for whom two separate DNA samples were available (taken at a mean difference of 5.5 years apart). These samples were taken from the baseline visit and one follow-up visit. As these measurements were performed in pairs (under the same technical conditions and parameters), no further technical adjustments were necessary. These measurements may not correspond to those for the same individuals within the main datasets (~F22190~, ~F22191~, ~F22192~) due to re-plating and re-measurement of the sample to produce the paired measurements for this specific analysis. For this reason, these data should be used independently of the main datasets and not in combination. Full details of this experiment can be found in Codd, V. et al (~Ehttps://doi.org/10.1101/2021.03.18.21253457~), and exemplar use of the derived regression dilution ratio can be found in Codd V et al (~Ehttps://doi.org/10.1101/2021.03.23.21253516~).

Researchers wishing to correct for regression dilution bias should use a correction factor of 0.65 for ~F22191~ and a correction factor of 0.68 for ~F22192~.

title: Liver iron (Fe)
notes:
Liver iron (Fe) derived from liver MRI scan.

Derived variable from application 9914. Use in the following publication:

Wilman HR, Kelly M, Garratt S, Matthews PM, Milanesi M, Herlihy A, et al. (2017) Characterisation of liver fat in the UK Biobank cohort. PLoS ONE 12(2): e0172921. doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0172921

title: Liver inflammation factor (LIF)
notes:
Liver inflammation factor (LIF) is measured on a scale of 0 to 4 where 0 is regarded as normal and 4 as indicating high fibrosis.

Derived variable from application 9914. Use in the following publication:

Wilman HR, Kelly M, Garratt S, Matthews PM, Milanesi M, Herlihy A, et al. (2017) Characterisation of liver fat in the UK Biobank cohort. PLoS ONE 12(2): e0172921. doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0172921

title: Proton density fat fraction (PDFF)
notes:
Liver fat percentage is defined as : fat / ( water + fat )

Derived variable from application 9914. Use in the following publication:

Wilman HR, Kelly M, Garratt S, Matthews PM, Milanesi M, Herlihy A, et al. (2017) Characterisation of liver fat in the UK Biobank cohort. PLoS ONE 12(2): e0172921. doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0172921

title: Anterior thigh fat-free muscle volume (right)
notes:
Anterior thigh includes quadriceps femoris, sartorius, and tensor fascia latae. Fat-free muscle volume (FFMV) is defined as the volume of all voxels with fat fraction <50% ('viable muscle tissue') in the thighs. This field replaces "Anterior thigh lean muscle volume (right)".

Values were recalculated and replaced for approximately 25,000 participants in 2021.

title: Posterior thigh fat-free muscle volume (right)
notes:
Posterior thigh include gluteus muscles, iliacus, adductor muscles, and hamstring muscles. Fat-free muscle volume (FFMV) is defined as the volume of all voxels with fat fraction <50% ('viable muscle tissue') in the thighs. This field replaces "Posterior thigh lean muscle volume (right)".

Values were recalculated and replaced for approximately 25,000 participants in 2021.

title: Anterior thigh fat-free muscle volume (left)
notes:
Anterior thigh includes quadriceps femoris, sartorius, and tensor fascia latae. Fat-free muscle volume (FFMV) is defined as the volume of all voxels with fat fraction <50% ('viable muscle tissue') in the thighs. This field replaces "Anterior thigh lean muscle volume (left)".

Values were recalculated and replaced for approximately 25,000 participants in 2021.

title: Posterior thigh fat-free muscle volume (left)
notes:
Posterior thigh include gluteus muscles, iliacus, adductor muscles, and hamstring muscles. Fat-free muscle volume (FFMV) is defined as the volume of all voxels with fat fraction <50% ('viable muscle tissue') in the thighs. This field replaces "Posterior thigh lean muscle volume (left)".

Values were recalculated and replaced for approximately 25,000 participants in 2021.

title: Visceral adipose tissue volume (VAT)
notes:
Adipose tissue within the abdominal cavity, excluding adipose tissue outside the abdominal skeletal muscles and adipose tissue and lipids within the cavity and posterior of the spine and back muscles.

Values were recalculated and replaced for approximately 25,000 participants in 2021.

title: Abdominal subcutaneous adipose tissue volume (ASAT)
notes:
Subcutaneous adipose tissue in the abdomen from the top of the femoral head to the top of the thoracic vertebrae T9.

Values were recalculated and replaced for approximately 25,000 participants in 2021.

title: Total thigh fat-free muscle volume
notes:
Anterior thigh includes quadriceps femoris, sartorius, and tensor fascia latae. Posterior thigh include gluteus muscles, iliacus, adductor muscles, and hamstring muscles. Fat-free muscle volume (FFMV) is defined as the volume of all voxels with fat fraction <50% ('viable muscle tissue') in the thighs. This field replaces "Total thigh muscle volume".

Values were recalculated and replaced for approximately 25,000 participants in 2021.

title: Total trunk fat volume
notes:
Total abdominal fat. Visceral adipose tissue (VAT) volume + abdominal subcutaneous adipose tissue (ASAT) volume.

Values were recalculated and replaced for approximately 25,000 participants in 2021.

title: VAT/ASAT error indicator
notes: VAT/ASAT error indicator, indicates that one or more slab(s) are missing in the torso region so that the data is not analysable for VAT/ASAT.

title: Thigh error indicator (left)
notes: Left thigh error indicator

title: Thigh error indicator (right)
notes: Right thigh error indicator

title: Image quality indicator
notes: General image quality indicator for VAT, ASAT and thigh measurements.

title: Total adipose tissue volume
notes: The total volume of adipose tissue, measured by MRI, between the bottom of the thigh muscles to the top of vertebrae T9.

title: Total lean tissue volume
notes: The total volume of lean tissue, measured by MRI, between the bottom of the thigh muscles to the top of vertebrae T9.

title: Liver iron corrected T1 (ct1)
notes:
Liver iron corrected T1 (ct1) is measure of liver inflammation and fibrosis. See Mojtahed A, et al. Abdom Radiol. 2019 Jan;44(1):72-84. doi: 10.1007/s00261-018-1701-2. PMID: 30032383

Derived variable provided by Perspectum (application #9914)

title: LV ejection fraction
notes:
Left ventricular ejection fraction

Please be aware that the inline VF results are fully automated without any expert quality control. Caution is advised to use results without any visual quality control or linear bias correction as recommended in the following paper: Fully-automated left ventricular mass and volume MRI analysis in the UK Biobank population cohort: evaluation of initial results. Suinesiaputra, A. et al. Int J Cardiovasc Imaging. 2018 (https://dx.doi.org/10.1007%2Fs10554-017-1225-9). Expert research groups are performing CMR analysis with quality control and these will be available in the Returns Catalogue.

title: Body surface area
notes:
This body surface area of the participant is estimated using the formula:
BSA = 0.20247 * (weight^0.425) * (height^0.725)

The height and weight are entered manually by the device operator and it is possible they differ from the values recorded in ~F50~ and ~F21002~.

title: Genotype intensities
notes:
Genotype intensities. Obtained using 
 gfetch 22430 -cN
where N is the chromosome number. Add -m flag to obtain the participant mapping file.

title: Genotype copy number variants, log2ratios
notes:
Genotype copy number variants, log2r. Obtained using

where N is the chromosome number. Add -m flag to obtain the participant mapping file.

title: Total abdominal adipose tissue index
notes:
Total abdominal fat divided by height squared: (visceral adipose tissue (VAT) volume + abdominal subcutaneous adipose tissue (ASAT) volume) / (height squared).

Values were recalculated and replaced for approximately 25,000 participants in 2021.

title: Weight-to-muscle ratio
notes:
Body weight divided by total thigh muscle volume: Body weight / total thigh fat-free muscle volume (FFMV).

Values were recalculated and replaced for approximately 25,000 participants in 2021.

title: Abdominal fat ratio
notes:
Total abdominal fat volume divided by total abdominal fat volume and thigh muscle volume: (visceral adipose tissue (VAT) volume + abdominal subcutaneous adipose tissue (ASAT) volume) / (visceral adipose tissue (VAT) volume + abdominal subcutaneous adipose tissue (ASAT) volume + total thigh fat-free muscle volume (FFMV)).

Values were recalculated and replaced for approximately 25,000 participants in 2021.

title: Muscle fat infiltration
notes:
Mean anterior thigh muscle fat infiltration. Anterior thigh includes quadriceps femoris, sartorius, and tensor fascia latae. Muscle fat infiltration is defined as the fat fraction in the 'viable muscle tissue' (fat-free muscle volume (FFMV)).

Values were recalculated and replaced for approximately 25,000 participants in 2021.

title: 10P Liver PDFF (proton density fat fraction)
notes: 10-point symmetric chemical-shift encoded acquisition (10P) liver proton density fat fraction (PDFF) measured as the average PDFF in up to nine (and at least three) regions of interest (ROI) in the liver. These ROI avoid inhomogeneities, major vessels and bile ducts. These values were derived based on the gradient echo imaging protocol (~F20203~). This field replaces "Liver proton density fat fraction (AMRA)".

title: Genotype copy number variants B-allele frequencies
notes:
Genotype copy number variants, baf. Obtained using 
 gfetch 22437 -cN
where N is the chromosome number. Add -m flag to obtain the participant mapping file.

notes:

where N is the chromosome number. Add -m flag to obtain the participant mapping file.

title: Work hours - lumped category
notes: Participants were asked "On average, how many hours a week did you work?". They were able to select a lumped category or enter a precise number of hours. This field captures the results for participants who selected a lumped category.

notes: Participants were asked "On average, how many hours a week did you work?". They were able to select a lumped category or enter a precise number of hours. This field captures the results for participants who entered a precise number.

title: Breathing problems during period of job
notes: Particpant asked: "When you had this job, did you have problems with your breathing?"

title: Job code - historical
notes:
Each self-coded job group was mapped to a 4-digit SOC2000 coding. In some cases several self-coded job groups map to the same SOC2000 coding as the input interface was designed to help untrained users classify their job according to the criteria/paths that would seem most natural to them.

It was not thought practical to ask participants to code their job to the more detailed levels of the SOC2000 coding.

title: Breathing problems improved/stopped away from workplace or on holiday
notes:
Participants who indicated they had breathing problems during a job were asked:
"Did these problems improve or stop when you were away from the workplace or on holiday?"

Question only asked if participant has value Yes in ~F22616~

title: Breathing problems responsible for leaving job
notes:
Participants who indicated they had breathing problems during a job were asked:
"Did you leave this job because of breathing problems?"

Question only asked if participant has value Yes in ~F22616~

title: Job involved shift work
notes:
Participants were asked: "Did you ever work shifts (day and/or night shifts) for this job?"

Day-shifts were defined as work in nomal daytime hours or morning, afternoon or evening work.

Night-shifts were defined as work for at least 3 hours between midnight and 5am.

title: Day shifts worked
notes:
Participants were asked: "Which shift pattern(s) did you follow for this job?"
Participants who indicated they worked day shifts were then asked: "Did you work day shifts for the whole of this job?"

Day-shifts were defined as work in nomal daytime hours or morning, afternoon or evening work.

title: Period spent working day shifts
notes: Participants who indicated they worked day shifts (but not for whole of job) were asked: "For how long did you work days shifts?"

title: Mixture of day and night shifts worked
notes:
Participants were asked: "Which shift pattern(s) did you follow for this job?"
Participants who indicated they worked a mixture of day and night shifts were then asked: "Did you work a mixture of day and night shifts for the whole of this job?"

Day-shifts were defined as work in nomal daytime hours or morning, afternoon or evening work.

Night-shifts were defined as work for at least 3 hours between midnight and 5am.

title: Period spent working mix of day and night shifts
notes: Participants who indicated they worked a mix of day and night shifts (but not for whole of job) were asked: "For how long did you work a mixture of day and night shifts?"

title: Usual length of each night shift during mixed shift periods
notes:
Participants who worked a mix of day and night shifts were asked:
"Please tell us about the most common night shift pattern you had during this time: How many hours was each night shift usually?"

title: Number of night shifts worked monthly during mixed shift periods
notes:
Participants who worked a mix of day and night shifts were asked:
"Please tell us about the most common night shift pattern you had during this time: How many night shifts a month did you usually work?"

title: Consecutive night shifts during mixed shift periods
notes:
Participants who worked a mix of day and night shifts were asked:
"Please tell us about the most common night shift pattern you had during this time: How many night shifts in a row did you usually work before a change of shift or rest day?"

title: Rest days during mixed shift periods
notes:
Participants who worked a mix of day and night shifts were asked:
"Please tell us about the most common night shift pattern you had during this time: How many rest days did you usually have after working a block of night shifts?"

title: Night shifts worked
notes:
Participants were asked: "Which shift pattern(s) did you follow for this job?"
Participants who indicated they worked night shifts were then asked: "Did you work night shifts for the whole of this job?"

Night-shifts were defined as work for at least 3 hours between midnight and 5am.

title: Period spent working night shifts
notes: Participants who indicated they worked night shifts (but not for whole of job) were asked: "For how long did you work night shifts?"

title: Usual length of each night shift during night shift periods
notes:
Participants who worked night shifts were asked:
"Please tell us about the most common night shift pattern you had during this time: How many hours was each night shift usually?"

title: Number of night shifts worked monthly during night shift periods
notes:
Participants who worked night shifts were asked:
"Please tell us about the most common night shift pattern you had during this time: How many night shifts a month did you usually work?"

title: Consecutive night shifts during night shift periods
notes:
Participants who worked night shifts were asked:
"Please tell us about the most common night shift pattern you had during this time: How many night shifts in a row did you usually work before a change of shift or rest day?"

title: Rest days during night shift periods
notes:
Participants who worked night shifts were asked:
"Please tell us about the most common night shift pattern you had during this time: How many rest days did you usually have after working a block of night shifts?"

title: Gap coding
notes: Participants were asked what they did in any periods when they were not working in paid employment for at least 20 hours each week. These periods were called "gaps".

title: Number of gap periods
notes: This is the number of distinct periods in which a participant was not working in paid employment for at least 20 hours each week.

notes: Participants who answered "other" in ~F22660~ were allowed to enter a free-text description of what they had been doing.

title: Home location at assessment - east co-ordinate (100m resolution)
notes:
This location information is based on the address where the participant lived at the time of their assessment.

The location co-ordinates use the Ordnance Survey (OSGB) reference. This East co-ordinate needs to be used in conjunction with the North co-ordinate in ~F22687~.

This field supersedes ~F20033~. The data has been updated to use more accurate geocoding data, based on the full address instead of the postcode alone.

These grid co-ordinates (to a 100m accuracy) will only be released following special approval. If access is approved, researchers will be required to hold these data-fields separately from their main project (a new set of encoded ids will be supplied) while they derive their required measures, which will then be made available to their main project only after these fields have been deleted.

For most purposes, grid co-ordinates rounded to a 1km accuracy will provide sufficient information on location of residence at assessment. These rounded values are found in ~F22688~ and ~F22689~.

title: Home location at assessment - north co-ordinate (100m resolution)
notes:
This location information is based on the address where the participant lived at the time of their assessment.

The location co-ordinates use the Ordnance Survey (OSGB) reference. This North co-ordinate needs to be used in conjunction with the East co-ordinate in ~F22686~.

This field supersedes ~F20034~. The data has been updated to use more accurate geocoding data where available, based on the full address instead of the postcode alone.

These grid co-ordinates (to a 100m accuracy) will only be released following special approval. If access is approved, researchers will be required to hold these data-fields separately from their main project (a new set of encoded ids will be supplied) while they derive their required measures, which will then be made available to their main project only after these fields have been deleted.

For most purposes, grid co-ordinates rounded to a 1km accuracy will provide sufficient information on location of residence at assessment. These rounded values are found in ~F22688~ and ~F22689~.

title: Home location at assessment - east co-ordinate (1km resolution)
notes:
This location information is based on the address where the participant lived at the time of their assessment.

The location co-ordinates use the Ordnance Survey (OSGB) reference. This East co-ordinate needs to be used in conjunction with the North co-ordinate in ~F22689~.

This field supersedes ~F20074~. The data has been updated to use more accurate geocoding data where available, based on the full address instead of the postcode alone. The data has also been corrected to use truncation (rounding down) instead of rounding, to derive the 1km resolution data.

These grid co-ordinates (to a 1km accuracy) will only be released following special approval.

For most purposes, these grid co-ordinates rounded to a 1km accuracy will provide sufficient information on location of residence at assessment. If a higher level of granularity is required, values are also available at a 100m resolution, which can be found in ~F22686~ and ~F22687~.

title: Home location at assessment - north co-ordinate (1km resolution)
notes:

The location co-ordinates use the Ordnance Survey (OSGB) reference. This North co-ordinate needs to be used in conjunction with the East co-ordinate in ~F22688~.

This field supersedes ~F20075~. The data has been updated to use more accurate geocoding data where available, based on the full address instead of the postcode alone. The data has also been corrected to use truncation (rounding down) instead of rounding, to derive the 1km resolution data.

These grid co-ordinates (to a 1km accuracy) will only be released following special approval.

For most purposes, these grid co-ordinates rounded to a 1km accuracy will provide sufficient information on location of residence at assessment. If a higher level of granularity is required, values are also available at a 100m resolution, which can be found in ~F22686~ and ~F22687~.

title: Date first recorded at location [obsolete]
notes:
This the date at which a participant is first recorded (according to the record sources available to UK Biobank) at the location given in ~F22702~ and ~F22704~ (or the more precise, but restricted, ~F22701~ and ~F22703~).

Note that, when data is supplied to approved researchers, the array index of dates will not necessarily be in the same order as the dates themselves as UK Biobank does not itself receive location data in chronological order.

Please be aware that there are some inherent inaccuracies in the date of a change of address as it will often correspond to the date the address was changed in the corresponding IT system, rather than the actual address change, due to delays in participants informing UK Biobank or external agencies that they have moved. In addition, we have identified a number of dates that have been incorrectly processed in the construction of data-field 22700 and which are up to 30 months different from the participant's change of address notification. We are working to correct this issue and will update the data-field in due course.

title: Home location - east co-ordinate (100m resolution) [obsolete]
notes:
This location information is based on the postcode for an address at which the participant is believed to have been resident, derived from a number of sources.

The location co-ordinates use the Ordnance Survey (OSGB) reference. This East co-ordinate needs to be used in conjunction with the North co-ordinate in ~F22703~.

These grid co-ordinates (to a 100m accuracy) will only be released following special approval. For most purposes, grid co-ordinates rounded to a 1Km distance will provide sufficient information on location of residence at assessment. These rounded values are found in ~F22702~ and ~F22704~.

title: Home location - east co-ordinate (1km resolution) [obsolete]
notes:
This location information is based on the postcode for an address at which the participant is believed to have been resident, derived from a number of sources.

The location co-ordinates use the Ordnance Survey (OSGB) reference, rounded to the nearest Kilometre. This East co-ordinate needs to be used in conjunction with the North co-ordinate in ~F22704~.

For most purposes, grid co-ordinates rounded to a 1Km distance will provide sufficient information on location of residence at assessment. Research proposals that require location details to a finer level of granularity (i.e. 100m) should request ~F22701~ and ~F22703~, however special approval will be required to release the more detailed information.

In some cases participants will appear to be at the same location at consecutive times. This occurs because there is a difference of under 1Km in the distance between two consecutive locations according to the more granular data.

title: HSV-1 seropositivity for Herpes Simplex virus-1
notes:
HSV-1 seropositivity for Herpes Simplex virus-1

Defined as positive if: antigen 1gG > 150.

title: HSV-2 seropositivity for Herpes Simplex virus-2
notes:
HSV-2 seropositivity for Herpes Simplex virus-2

Defined as positive if: antigen 2mgG unique > 150.

title: VZV seropositivity for Varicella Zoster Virus
notes:
VZV seropositivity for Varicella Zoster Virus

Defined as positive if: antigen gE / gl > 100.

title: EBV seropositivity for Epstein-Barr Virus
notes:
EBV seropositivity for Epstein-Barr Virus

Defined as positive if: two or more of antigen VCA p18 > 250, antigen EBNA-1 > 250, antigen ZEBRA > 100, antigen EA-D > 100.

title: CMV seropositivity for Human Cytomegalovirus
notes:
CMV seropositivity for Human Cytomegalovirus

Defined as positive if: two or more of antigen pp150 Nter > 100, antigen pp 52 > 150, antigen pp 28 > 200.

title: HHV-6 overall seropositivity for Human Herpesvirus-6
notes:
HHV-6 overall seropositivity for Human Herpesvirus-6

Defined as positive if: one or more of antigen IE1A > 100, antigen IE1B > 100, antigen p101 k > 100.

title: HHV-6A seropositivity for Human Herpesvirus-6
notes:
HHV-6A seropositivity for Human Herpesvirus-6

Defined as positive if: antigen IE1A > 100.

title: HHV-6B seropositivity for Human Herpesvirus-6
notes:
HHV-6B seropositivity for Human Herpesvirus-6

Defined as positive if: antigen IE1B > 100.

title: HHV-7 seropositivity for Human Herpesvirus-7
notes:
HHV-7 seropositivity for Human Herpesvirus-7

Defined as positive if: antigen U14 > 100.

title: KSHV seropositivity for Kaposi's Sarcoma-Associated Herpesvirus
notes:
KSHV seropositivity for Kaposi's Sarcoma-Associated Herpesvirus

Defined as positive if: either antigen LANA > 100 or antigen K8.1 > 175.

title: HBV seropositivity for Hepatitis B Virus
notes:
HBV seropositivity for Hepatitis B Virus

Defined as positive if: both antigen HBc > 100 and antigen HBe > 150.

title: HCV seropositivity for Hepatitis C Virus
notes:
HCV seropositivity for Hepatitis C Virus

Defined as positive if: both antigen Core > 150 and antigen NS3 > 150.

Defined as positive if: either antigen p22 > 100 or antigen sag1 > 160.

title: HTLV-1 seropositivity for Human T-Lymphotropic Virus 1
notes:
HTLV-1 seropositivity for Human T-Lymphotropic Virus 1

Defined as positive if: either antigen HTLV-1 gag > 1500 or antigen HTLV-1 env > 150.

title: HIV-1 seropositivity for Human Immunodeficiency Virus
notes:
HIV-1 seropositivity for Human Immunodeficiency Virus

Defined as positive if: both antigen HIV-1 gag > 600 and antigen HIV-1 env > 150.

title: BKV seropositivity for Human Polyomavirus BKV
notes:
BKV seropositivity for Human Polyomavirus BKV

Defined as positive if: antigen BK VP1 > 250.

title: JCV seropositivity for Human Polyomavirus JCV
notes:
JCV seropositivity for Human Polyomavirus JCV

Defined as positive if: antigen JC VP1 > 250.

title: MCV seropositivity for Merkel Cell Polyomavirus
notes:
MCV seropositivity for Merkel Cell Polyomavirus

Defined as positive if: antigen MC VP1 > 250.

title: HPV 16 Definition I seropositivity for Human Papillomavirus type-16
notes:
HPV 16 Definition I seropositivity for Human Papillomavirus type-16

Defined as positive if: antigen L1 > 175.

title: HPV 18 seropositivity for Human Papillomavirus type-18
notes:
HPV 18 seropositivity for Human Papillomavirus type-18

Defined as positive if: antigen L1 > 175.

title: C. trachomatis Definition I seropositivity for Chlamydia trachomatis
notes:
C. trachomatis Definition I seropositivity for Chlamydia trachomatis

Defined as positive if: antigen pGP3 > 200.

title: C. trachomatis Definition II seropositivity for Chlamydia trachomatis
notes:
C. trachomatis Definition II seropositivity for Chlamydia trachomatis

Defined as positive if: two or more of (the maximum of antigen momp A and antigen momp D) > 100, tarp-D F1 > 100, tarp-D F2 > 100, porB > 80.

Data is only provided for this field in cases where the participant is seronegative under Definition I in ~F23070~, which should used be used as the main definition for seropositivity for Chlamydia trachomatis.

title: Downhearted and depressed over last week
notes:
Participants were asked:

"Over the past week have you: Felt downhearted and depressed?"

title: H. pylori Definition I seropositivity for Helicobacter pylori
notes:
H. pylori Definition I seropositivity for Helicobacter pylori

Defined as positive if: two or more of antigen CagA > 400, antigen VacA > 100, antigen OMP > 170, antigen GroEL > 80, antigen Catalase > 180, antigen UreA > 130.

title: H. pylori Definition II seropositivity for Helicobacter pylori
notes:
H. pylori Definition II seropositivity for Helicobacter pylori

Defined as positive if: two or more of antigen VacA > 100, antigen OMP > 170, antigen GroEL > 80, antigen Catalase > 180, antigen UreA > 130.

The CagA antigen was excluded from the data generated in the 2nd week because of a lab-based handling mistake. Hence, this second definition is available without the CagA antigen.

title: HPV 16 Definition II seropositivity for Human Papillomavirus type-16
notes:
HPV 16 Definition II seropositivity for Human Papillomavirus type-16

Defined as positive if: either antigen E6 > 120 or antigen E7 > 150.

title: Happy over last week
notes:
Participants were asked:

"Over the past week have you: Been happy?"

title: Device used for typing
notes:
Participants were asked:

"How are you typing characters into the computer?"

This was done because the device characteristics may have an affect on the speed of their subsequent actions in the cognitive tests.

title: Device used for pointing
notes:
Participants were asked:

"What are you using to point on the screen?"

This was done because the device characteristics may have an affect on the speed of their subsequent actions in the cognitive tests.

title: When mood described
notes: Indicates the time that a participant connected to the online questionnaire system and described their mood over the last week prior to completing the cognitive questionnaire. Note that participants could complete the section of the cognitive questionnaire over multiple sessions so some people have multiple values for this field which must be linked to the individual sections by examing their timestamps.

title: Sequencing Provider [200k release]
notes: Sequencing provider for each sample in the WGS project.

title: Sample plate ID [200k release]
notes: Sequencing provider plate barcode. A 10 digit alphanumeric EAN13 standard GS1 type linear barcode format orientated on the long side of the plate.

title: Shipment batch number [200k release]
notes: Numerical shipment identifier. Batch numbers increase consecutively from Batch 1 for each sequencing provider.

title: Sample quant reading (UKB) [200k release]
notes: Sample concentration of normalised sample as measured by UKB.

title: Sample quant reading (sequence provider) [200k release]
notes: Sample concentration as measured by sequencing providers.

title: Library prep plate barcode [200k release]
notes: Barcode of SBS format plate used during library preparation.

title: Library prep plate position (well) [200k release]
notes: Row and column position on library plate, e.g. A01

title: Yield [200k release]
notes: Sequence data quantity

title: Proportion of mapped read pairs [200k release]
notes: Percentage of mapped read-pairs with appropriate orientation and separation. Threshold is >=95% of the total mapped reads

title: Coverage [200k release]
notes: Percentage of autosome sequenced to >=15X

title: Average batch coverage [200k release]
notes: The mean sample genome coverage across the montly sequencing batch to deliver 95% of the autosome covered to >=15X, is expected to be approximately 30X across the genome with a min coverage of 26X

title: Freemix verify BAM ID [200k release]
notes: Freemix percentage value of sample contamination levels

title: NRD genotyping [200k release]
notes: Sample discordance levels at non-reference genotypes.

title: Quality requirements achieved [200k release]
notes: Pass/fail flag indicating whether generated sequence data has met all quality thresholds.

title: Read haps [200k release]
notes: Read haps estimation of contamination. This is mandatory for contamination failed samples but optional for passed samples.

Note that, unlike the genotyped and imputed information, all of the data for the whole genome is stored in a single file with properties:

title: Blood-type haplotype
notes:
Blood type was imputed for genotyped UK Biobank participants using three SNPs (rs505922, rs8176719, and rs8176746) in the ABO gene on chromosome 9q34.2.

rs8176719 deletion was taken as indicative of haplotype O;
For participants with no result for rs8176719, rs505922 of T was used to indicate type O.
Type B was indicated by T at rs8176746.

This was developed from the methodology of:

  • Melzer et al 2008 (https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pgen.1000072)
  • Pare et al 2008 (https:// doi.org/10.1371/journal.pgen.1000118)
  • Wolpin et al 2010 (https:// doi.org/10.1158/0008-5472.CAN-09-2993)
  • Groot et al 2020 (https://doi.org/10.1161/ATVBAHA.119.313658)

title: Whole genome variant call files (VCFs) and indices [200k release]
notes: Per-participant variant call files (gVCFs) generated in the Vanguard and Main Phases of the Whole Genome Sequencing project using GATK. Initial data for 200,000 participants was released in November 2021.

title: Whole genome CRAM files and indices [200k release]
notes: Per-participant CRAM files generated in the Vanguard and Main Phases of the Whole Genome Sequencing project. Initial data for 200,000 participants was released in November 2021.

title: Whole genome GraphTyper joint call pVCF (deprecated)
notes: Whole genome graph-typer

title: Whole genome GATK joint call pVCF
notes:
Joint variant calling for the first 150,000 participants sequenced in the main phase of the whole genome sequencing project. This joint variant call was performed using GATK.

This data is now deprecated and superceded by ~F24304~. No further joint variant calls using GATK pipelines are planned.

title: BQSR - GATK BaseRecalibrator [200k release]
notes: Base quality score recalibration (BQSR) performed using GATK BaseRecalibrator as part of genome assembly. Documentation of this tool is provided here (~Ehttps://gatk.broadinstitute.org/hc/en-us/articles/360036898312-BaseRecalibrator~) This step was performed for all samples sequenced in the main phase of the whole genome sequencing project.

title: Sample Contamination (ReadHaps) [200k release]
notes: Estimation of human contamination in whole genome sequencing data, generated using ReadHaps software (~Ehttps://github.com/DecodeGenetics/read_haps~). This is provided for all samples sequenced by deCODE, and for any samples sequenced by Wellcome Sanger Institute with a calculated sample contamination over 1% using Freemix VerifyBamID

title: Genotype Concordance - Contingency Metrics [200k release]
notes: Non-reference genotype concordance contingency metrics generated on samples sequenced by deCODE Genetics in the main phase of the whole genome sequencing project, using Picard tools.

title: Values wanted
notes: This is an array of values indicating the digit that the participant would have entered if they had correctly matched the symbols above and below.

title: Values entered
notes: Digits entered by participant

title: Number of symbol digit matches attempted
notes: Number of symbol digit matches attempted before the participant timed-out.

title: Number of symbol digit matches made correctly
notes:
This is the number of symbols correctly matched to digits by the participant.

Note that it would be possible to get a high score here simply by repeated entering "1" very quickly as it would be correct 1/8 of the time and a large number of attempts could be made. For this reason, the score must be interpreted alongside ~F6774~ which shows the total number of attempts.

title: Genotype Concordance - Summary Metrics (Picard) [200k release]
