title: Genotype Concordance [200k release]
notes: Non-reference discordance calculated for samples sequenced by WSI as part of the main phase of the whole genome sequencing project

title: Concatenated QC Metrics [200k release]
notes: Concatenated quality control (QC) metrics produced on samples sequenced by deCODE genetics as part of the sequencing and assembly process.

title: Sample Contamination (verifyBamID) - depthSM [200k release]
notes: Estimation of human contamination in whole genome sequencing data, generated using Freemix VerifyBamID.

title: Sample Contamination (verifyBamID) - selfSM [200k release]
notes: Estimation of human contamination in whole genome sequencing data, generated using Freemix VerifyBamID.

title: Manta-called scored structural variant and indel candidates [Vanguard 50k release]
notes:
Structural variant and indel candidates identified in non-joint called data using Illumina Manta (~Ehttps://github.com/Illumina/manta/blob/master/docs/userGuide/README.md#configuration~).

Note that this data was produced as part of the Vanguard phase of the whole genome sequencng project, and is not generated for participants sequenced in the main phase.

title: Manta-called unscored structural variant and indel candidates [Vanguard 50k release]
notes:
Structural variant and indel candidates identified in non-joint called data using Illumina Manta (~Ehttps://github.com/Illumina/manta/blob/master/docs/userGuide/README.md#configuration~).

Note that this data was produced as part of the Vanguard phase of the whole genome sequencng project, and is not generated for participants sequenced in the main phase.

title: Population level WGS variants, pVCF format - interim 150k release
notes: Joint variant calling for the first 150,000 participants sequenced in the main phase of the whole genome sequencing project. This joint variant calling was performed by deCODE Genetics using a GraphTyper pipeline. The data is provided in a pVCF format.

title: Whole genome GraphTyper SV data - interim 150k release
notes: Structural variant data generated as part of the GraphTyper joint variant calling on the first 150,000 participants sequenced in the main phase.

title: Whole genome GraphTyper SV data [500k release]
notes: Structural variant data generated as part of the GraphTyper joint variant calling.

title: Posterior thigh muscle fat infiltration (MFI) (left)
notes: Posterior thigh include gluteus muscles, iliacus, adductor muscles, and hamstring muscles. Muscle fat infiltration is defined as the fat fraction in the viable muscle tissue (fat-free muscle volume (FFMV)).

title: Posterior thigh muscle fat infiltration (MFI) (right)
notes: Posterior thigh include gluteus muscles, iliacus, adductor muscles, and hamstring muscles. Muscle fat infiltration is defined as the fat fraction in the viable muscle tissue (fat-free muscle volume (FFMV)).

title: Microsatellites - 150k release
notes: Microsatellite data generated using a specially optimised tool (popSTR) for microsatellite (STR) marker calling in whole-genome sequencing studies. This dataset includes pVCF files featuring STR marker calls for 150,119 participants. Documentation on popSTR is available here ~Ehttps://doi.org/10.1093/bioinformatics/btw568~.

title: Whole genome GATK variant call files (VCFs) and indices [500k release]
notes: Per-participant variant call files (gVCFs) generated in the Vanguard and Main Phases of the Whole Genome Sequencing project.

title: Whole genome GATK CRAM files and indices [500k release]
notes: Per-participant CRAM files generated in the Vanguard and Main Phases of the Whole Genome Sequencing project.

title: GraphTyper population level WGS variants, pVCF format [500k release]
notes: Whole genome joint variant call, generated using GraphTyper.

title: Whole genome GATK joint call pVCF (reserved)
notes: Whole genome, joint call pVCFS

title: BQSR - GATK BaseRecalibrator [500k release]
notes: Base quality score recalibration (BQSR) performed using GATK BaseRecalibrator as part of genome assembly. Documentation of this tool is provided here (~Ehttps://gatk.broadinstitute.org/hc/en-us/articles/360036898312-BaseRecalibrator~) This step was performed for all samples sequenced in the main phase of the whole genome sequencing project.

title: Sample Contamination (ReadHaps) [500k release]
notes: Estimation of human contamination in whole genome sequencing data, generated using ReadHaps software (~Ehttps://github.com/DecodeGenetics/read_haps~). This is provided for all samples sequenced by deCODE, and for any main phase samples sequenced by Wellcome Sanger Institute with a calculated sample contamination over 1% using Freemix VerifyBamID.

title: Genotype Concordance - Contingency Metrics [500k release]

title: Genotype Concordance - Detail Metrics [500k release]
notes: Non-reference genotype concordance detailed metrics generated on samples sequenced by deCODE Genetics in the main phase of the whole genome sequencing project, using Picard tools.

title: Genotype Concordance - Summary Metrics (Picard) [500k release]
notes: Non-reference genotype concordance detailed metrics generated on samples sequenced by deCODE Genetics in the main phase of the whole genome sequencing project, using Picard tools.

title: Genotype Concordance [500k release]
notes: Non-reference discordance calculated for samples sequenced by WSI as part of the main phase of the whole genome sequencing project.

title: Concatenated QC Metrics [500k release]
notes:
Concatenated quality control (QC) metrics produced on samples sequenced by deCODE genetics as part of the sequencing and assembly process.

This data is currently restricted and is anticipated for public release in late 2023.

notes: Nitrogen oxides; Land Use Regression (LUR) estimate for annual average 2010.

title: Particulate matter air pollution (pm10); 2010
notes: PM10 (particulate matter with diameter less than or equal to 10 micrometres); Land Use Regression (LUR) estimate for annual average 2010.

title: Particulate matter air pollution (pm2.5); 2010
notes: PM10 (particulate matter with diameter less than or equal to 2.5 micrometres); Land Use Regression (LUR) estimate for annual average 2010.

title: Particulate matter air pollution (pm2.5) absorbance; 2010
notes: PM2.5 absorbance. This is ameasurement of the blackness of PM2.5 filters; a proxy for elemental carbon, which is the dominant light absorbing substanc. Land Use Regression (LUR) estimate for annual average 2010

title: Particulate matter air pollution 2.5-10um; 2010
notes: PM coarse (particulate matter betweem 2.5 and 10 micrometres); Land Use Regression (LUR) estimate for annual average 2010.

title: Traffic intensity on the nearest road
notes: Traffic intensity (average total number of motor vehicles per 24 hours) on the nearest road based upon local road network measured in vehicles per day. Traffic count data is from the Road Traffic Statistics Branch at the Department for Transport attached to the local road network. Traffic data for unmonitored links were estimates based on surrounding monitored links. The minimum traffic count was set to 500 vehicles per day. The local road network is taken from the Ordnance Survey Meridian 2 road network (scale 1:50000, 1 metre accuracy), 2009.

title: Inverse distance to the nearest road
notes: Inverse distance to the nearest road based upon local road network. The local road network is taken from the Ordnance Survey Meridian 2 road network (scale 1:50000, 1 metre accuracy), 2009.

title: Traffic intensity on the nearest major road
notes: Traffic intensity is the average total number of motor vehicles per 24 hours on the nearest major road based upon a local road network. Traffic count data is from the Road Traffic Statistics Branch at the Department for Transport attached to the local road network. Traffic data for unmonitored links were estimates based on surrounding monitored links. The local road network is taken from the Ordnance Survey Meridian 2 road network (scale 1:50000, 1 metre accuracy), 2009. The definition of a major road for the local road network is a road with traffic intensity greater than 5000 motor vehicles per 24 hours.

title: Inverse distance to the nearest major road
notes: Inverse distance to the nearest major road based upon a local road network. The definition of a major road for the local road network is a road with traffic intensity greater than 5000 motor vehicles per 24 hours. The local road network is taken from the Ordnance Survey Meridian 2 road network (scale 1:50000, 1 metre accuracy), 2009.

title: Total traffic load on major roads
notes: Total traffic load (average total number of motor vehicles per 24 hours * length of road segment) on major roads in a 100 metres circular buffer of residential address based upon local road network. The definition of a major road for the local road network is a road with traffic intensity greater than 5000 motor vehicles per 24 hours. The local road network is taken from the Ordnance Survey Meridian 2 road network (scale 1:50000, 1 metre accuracy), 2009.

title: Close to major road
notes: Indicator variable indicating whether a residential address is within 50 metres of a class 1 or 2 type road and/or within 100 metres of a class 0 road, based upon central road network. The Central road network is taken from Eurostreets version 3.1 digital road network (scale 1:10000), derived from the TeleAtlas MultiNet TM dataset for the year 2008. All roads of class 0, 1 and 2 (motorways, main roads of major importance and other main roads) were classified as major roads. Based upon local knowledge classes 3 and 4 (secondary roads and local connecting roads) were also classified as major roads.

title: Sum of road length of major roads within 100m
notes: Sum of road length of major roads from the central road network within a 100 metre circular buffer of residential address. The Central road network is taken from Eurostreets version 3.1 digital road network (scale 1:10000), derived from the TeleAtlas MultiNet TM dataset for the year 2008. All roads of class 0, 1and 2 (motorways, main roads of major importance and other main roads) were classified as major roads. Based upon local knowledge classes 3 and 4 (secondary roads and local connecting roads) were also classified as major roads.

title: Average daytime sound level of noise pollution
notes: LDay (day equivalent level): Average sound level pressure LAeq over the 12-hour period 07:00 to 19:00.

title: Average evening sound level of noise pollution
notes: LEve (evening equivalent level): Average sound level pressure LAeq between the hours of 19:00 to 23:00.

title: Average night-time sound level of noise pollution
notes: LNight (night equivalent level): Average sound level pressure LAeq overnight 23:00 to 07:00.

title: Average 16-hour sound level of noise pollution
notes: LAeq,16hr (A-weighted equivalent sound level): Average sound level pressure LAeq between the hours of 07:00 to 23:00.

title: Average 24-hour sound level of noise pollution
notes: LDen: (day-evening-night equivalent level): A-weighted Leq noise level measured over the 24 hour period with a 10 decibel penality added to the levels between 23:00 and 07:00.

title: Included in pollution study
notes: This field indicates whether a participant was included in the residential air/noise pollution studies. Participants without a value here were not in the studies.

title: GraphTyper population level WGS variants, pVCF format [200k release]
notes: Joint variant calling for the first 150,000 participants sequenced in the main phase of the whole genome sequencing project, together with the 50,000 participants sequenced during the Vanguard phase. This joint variant calling was performed by deCODE Genetics using a GraphTyper pipeline. The data is provided in a pVCF format.

title: GraphTyper population level WGS variants, PLINK format [200k release]
notes: Plink (version 1; BED format) population level formatted files derived from joint variant call (pVCF) files produced using the GraphTyper pipeline. This format conversion was performed by UK Biobank from the 200,000 participant joint variant call data in ~F24304~

title: GraphTyper population level genome variants, BGEN format [200k release]
notes: BGEN binary format population level formatted files derived from joint variant call (pVCF) files produced using the GraphTyper pipeline. BGEN files are Zlib compressed, as produced by PLINK 2. This format conversion was performed by UK Biobank from the 200,000 participant joint variant call data in ~F24304~.

title: FR liver PDFF mean
notes: Fat referenced (FR) liver proton density fat fraction (PDFF) measured as the average PDFF in up to nine (and at least three) regions of interest (ROI) in the liver. These ROI avoid inhomogeneities, major vessels, and bile ducts. These values were derived based on the IDEAL imaging protocol (~F20254~).

title: Anterior thigh muscle fat infiltration (MFI) (left)
notes: Anterior thigh includes quadriceps femoris, sartorius, and tensor fascia latae. Muscle fat infiltration is defined as the fat fraction in the viable muscle tissue (fat-free muscle volume (FFMV)).

title: Anterior thigh muscle fat infiltration (MFI) (right)
notes: Anterior thigh includes quadriceps femoris, sartorius, and tensor fascia latae. Muscle fat infiltration is defined as the fat fraction in the viable muscle tissue (fat-free muscle volume (FFMV)).

title: T1 acquisition protocol versions
notes:
Acquisition protocol version provides a confound representing the "Study description" field in the T1 DICOMs. The UK Biobank imaging project has some variance in the naming convention of the study description field (e.g. upper/lower case). This variance has been standardised in the creation of this variable.

The variance in the naming convention of the "Study description" field correlates with acquisition date, but is not reliably ordered according to acquisition date.

Resource 2066 indicates the linkage between each Acquisition_protocol_version and the Dicom_study_description. Details of the first occurence and the frequency of occurrence of each acquisition protocol version are also provided.

title: Greenspace percentage, buffer 1000m
notes:
The percentage of the home location buffer classed as 'Greenspace', as a proportion of all land-use types, and with home location data buffered at 1000m.

Land use data were obtained from the Generalized land use database for England (GLUD) 2005 data at the 2001 Census Output Area level. Each home location polygon was then allocated an area weighted mean of the land use percentage coverage for the 2001 Census Output Areas intersecting the home location buffer. Data are only available for participants whose home location was in England.

Further details of the methods used to derive these data can be found in ~R15374~, where this field is derived from variables referred to as gs1000_0 and gs1000_1.

title: Natural environment percentage, buffer 1000m
notes:
The percentage of the home location buffer classed as 'Natural Environment' in the Land Cover Map (LCM) 2007, and with home location data buffered at 1000m.

Land use data were obtained from the Land Cover Map, 2007, and the 23 land cover classes were reclassified to a binary classification; classes 1-2 ('Natural Environment'), and 22-23 ('Built environment').

Further details of the methods used to derive these data can be found in ~R15374~, where this field is derived from variables referred to as ne1000_0 and ne1000_1.

title: Distance (Euclidean) to coast

title: Scanner lateral (X) brain position
notes:
The exact location of the head and the radio-frequency receive coil in the scanner can affect data quality and imaging-derived phenotypes. To help account for variations in position in different scanned participants, several variables have been generated which describe aspects of the positioning and can be used as "confounding variables" - for example they might be regressed out of brain phenotypes before carrying out correlations between these and non-imaging variables.

The lateral brain position is the X-co-ordinate (left-right) of the centre of the brain mask within the scanner.

title: Scanner transverse (Y) brain position
notes:
The exact location of the head and the radio-frequency receive coil in the scanner can affect data quality and imaging-derived phenotypes. To help account for variations in position in different scanned participants, several variables have been generated which describe aspects of the positioning and can be used as "confounding variables" - for example they might be regressed out of brain phenotypes before carrying out correlations between these and non-imaging variables.

The transverse brain position is the Y-co-ordinate (front-back relative to head) of the back of the brain mask within the scanner.

title: Scanner longitudinal (Z) brain position
notes:
The exact location of the head and the radio-frequency receive coil in the scanner can affect data quality and imaging-derived phenotypes. To help account for variations in position in different scanned participants, several variables have been generated which describe aspects of the positioning and can be used as "confounding variables" - for example they might be regressed out of brain phenotypes before carrying out correlations between these and non-imaging variables.

The longitudinal brain position is the Z-co-ordinate of the centre of the brain mask within the scanner. The Z axis points down the centre of the magnet.

title: Scanner table position
notes:
The exact location of the head and the radio-frequency receive coil in the scanner can affect data quality and imaging-derived phenotypes. To help account for variations in position in different scanned participants, several variables have been generated which describe aspects of the positioning and can be used as "confounding variables" - for example they might be regressed out of brain phenotypes before carrying out correlations between these and non-imaging variables.

The table position is the Z-co-ordinate of the coil (and the scanner table that the coil sits on) within the scanner. The Z axis points down the centre of the magnet.

title: IDP pipeline version
notes:
The array index value indicates the version number of the machine learning pipeline used to generate the derived data. Atrial volume calculations required Python libraries to extract segmentation boundaries, approximately evaluating a 3D volume by assuming an ellipsoid object. An upgrade to these libraries introduced some numerical differences in a small subset of participants. Where multiple values were provided, the most recent version of the segmentation has been retained.

Array 0: Data derived in 2020 and published in ~Ehttps://doi.org/10.1038/s41591-020-1009-y~.

Array 1: Data derived in 2021 after update of Python libraries.

title: Arterial spin labelling brain images - NIFTI
notes:
Arterial Spin Labelling images in NIFTI format. The source DICOM image was acquired using the following parameters:
  • Resolution: 3.4x3.4x4.5 mm
  • Field-of-view: 64x48x32 matrix
  • Scan duration: 2 minutes
  • Preparation: Multi-postlabelling delay pseudocontinuous arterial spin labelling, labelling duration 1800 ms, postlabelling delays 400, 800, 1200, 1600 and 2000 ms, labelling plane offset from the centre of the imaging volume 90 mm
  • Readout: 2-shot segmented 3D-GRASE, left-right phase encoding, refocussing flip angle 120
  • Background suppression: pre-saturation and two inversion pulses (to null tissues with T1 = 700 ms and 1400 ms, 100 ms prior to excitation)
  • Volumes: one label/control pair per postlabelling delay plus one calibration (M0) volume without labelling or background suppression (effective TR 5000 ms).
The average size of these NIFTI datasets is 75MB per participant.

title: Quantitative susceptibility mapping images - NIFTI
notes:
Quantitative susceptibility mapping images (derived from swMRI data) in NIFTI format. The source swMRI DICOM image was acquired using the following parameters:
  • Resolution: 0.8x0.8x3 mm
  • Field-of-view: 256x288x48 matrix
  • Duration: 2.5 minutes
  • Two echos, TE=9.42,20 ms
  • 3D, axial, in-plane acceleration iPAT=2, partial Fourier = 7/8, prescan-normalise
The average size of these NIFTI datasets is 25 MB per participant.

title: Specific cognitive ability (AS)
notes: Estimate of each persons cognitive ability when performing the picture vocabulary task. Value has been scaled to the range 0-1.

title: Response delay interval
notes: Estimates the basic visuomotor processing times of a participant (i.e. regardless of the actual cognitive difficulty of the trial).

title: Index of Multiple Deprivation (England)
notes:
The English Indices of Deprivation 2010 are measures of multiple deprivation at the small area level. The model of multiple deprivation which underpins the Indices of Deprivation 2010 is based on the idea of distinct domains of deprivation which can be recognised and measured separately. These domains are experienced by individuals living in an area. People may be counted in one or more of the domains, depending on the number of types of deprivation that they experience.

Each domain represents a specific form of deprivation experienced by people and each can be measured individually using a number of indicators. Seven distinct domains have been identified in the English Indices of Deprivation; Income Deprivation, Employment Deprivation, Health Deprivation and Disability, Education Skills and Training Deprivation, Barriers to Housing and Services, Living Environment Deprivation, and Crime. Individual domains can be used in isolation as measures of each specific form of deprivation. They can also be combined, using appropriate weights, into a single overall Index of Multiple Deprivation which can be used to rank every small area in England according to the deprivation experienced by the people living there. Along with two supplementary indices, Income Deprivation Affecting Children Index and Income Deprivation Affecting Older People Index, they form the English Indices of Deprivation. These statistics allow the most, and least, deprived areas of the country to be identified as well as providing information about the issues faced by people living in different parts of the country.

title: Income score (England)
notes:
This domain measures the proportion of the population in an area experiencing deprivation related to low income. A combined count of income deprived individuals per LSOA is calculated by summing the following five indicators:
  • Adults and children in Income Support families
  • Adults and children in Income-Based Jobseeker's Allowance families
  • Adults and children in Pension Credit (Guarantee) families
  • Adults and children in Child Tax Credit families (who are not in receipt of Income Support, Income-Based Jobseeker's Allowance or Pension Credit) whose equivalised income (excluding housing benefits) is below 60 per cent of the median before housing costs
  • Asylum seekers in England in receipt of subsistence support, accommodation support, or both.

title: Employment score (England)
notes:
This domain measures employment deprivation in an area conceptualised as involuntary exclusion of the working age population from the labour market. A combined count of employment deprived individuals per LSOA is calculated by summing the following seven indicators:
  • Claimants of Jobseeker's Allowance (both Contributory and Income-Based) women aged 18-59 and men aged 18-64, averaged over 4 quarters
  • Claimants of Incapacity Benefit women aged 18-59 and men aged 18-64, averaged over 4 quarters
  • Claimants of Severe Disablement Allowance women aged 18-59 and men aged 18-64, averaged over 4 quarters
  • Claimants of Employment Support Allowance women aged 18-59 and men aged 18-64
  • Participants in New Deal for the 18-24s who are not in receipt of Jobseeker's Allowance, averaged over 4 quarters
  • Participants in New Deal for 25+ who are not in receipt of Jobseeker's Allowance, averaged over 4 quarters
  • Participants in New Deal for Lone Parents (after initial interview) aged over 18, averaged over 4 quarters.

title: Health score (England)
notes:
This domain measures premature death and the impairment of quality of life by poor health. It considers both physical and mental health. The domain measures morbidity, disability and premature mortality but not aspects of behaviour or environment that may be predictive of future health deprivation. Four indicators are used to calculate this domain:
  • Years of Potential Life Lost - an age and sex standardised measure of premature death
  • Comparative Illness and Disability Ratio - an age and sex standardised measure of morbidity and disability
  • Measures of acute morbidity - an age and sex standardised rate of emergency admissions to hospital
  • Proportion of adults under 60 suffering from mood or anxiety disorders - a modelled indicator for the proportion of adults suffering from mood and anxiety disorders.

title: Education score (England)
notes:
This domain measures the extent of deprivation in terms of education, skills and training in an area. The indicators are structured into two sub-domains: one relating to children and young people and one relating to adult skills. These two sub-domains are designed to reflect the 'flow' and 'stock' of educational disadvantage within an area respectively. Seven indicators are used to calculate this domain:
  • Average points score of pupils taking English, Maths and Science Key Stage 2 exams
  • Average points score of pupils taking English, Maths and Science Key Stage 3 exams
  • Average capped points score of pupils taking Key Stage 4 (GCSE or equivalent) exams
  • Proportion of young people not staying on in school or non-advanced education above age 16
  • Secondary school absence rate - the proportion of authorised and unauthorised absences from secondary school
  • Proportion of those aged under 21 not entering Higher Education.
  • Proportion of adults aged 25-54 with no or low qualifications.

title: Housing score (England)
notes:
This domain measures the physical and financial accessibility of housing and key local services. The indicators fall into two sub-domains: 'geographical barriers', which relate to the physical proximity of local services, and 'wider barriers' which includes issues relating to access to housing such as affordability. Seven indicators are combined to calculate this domain:
  • Household overcrowding - the proportion of households within an LSOA which are judged to have insufficient space to meet the household's needs
  • Homelessness - the rate of acceptances for housing assistance under the homelessness provisions of the 1996 Housing Act (at local authority district level)
  • Difficulty of access to owner-occupation (local authority district level) - proportion of households aged under 35 whose income means they are unable to afford to enter owner occupation
  • Road distance to a GP surgery
  • Road distance to a supermarket or convenience store
  • Road distance to a primary school
  • Road distance to a Post Office.

title: Crime score (England)
notes:
This domain measures the rate of recorded crime in an area for four major crime types representing the risk of personal and material victimisation at a small area level.
  • Violence - number of reported violent crimes (19 reported crime types) per 1000 at risk population
  • Burglary - number of reported burglaries (4 reported crime types) per 1000 at risk population
  • Theft - number of reported thefts (5 reported crime types) per 1000 at risk population
  • Criminal damage - number of reported crimes (11 reported crime types) per 1000 at risk population.

title: Living environment score (England)
notes:
This domain measures the quality of individuals' immediate surroundings both within and outside the home. The indicators fall into two sub-domains: the 'indoors' living environment, which measures the quality of housing, and the 'outdoors' living environment which contains two measures relating to air quality and road traffic accidents. Four indicators are combined to calculate this domain:
  • Social and private housing in poor condition
  • Houses with central heating
  • Air quality
  • Road traffic accidents.

title: Income score (Wales)
notes:
The purpose of this domain is to capture the extent of deprivation relating to income at a small area level across Wales. It focuses on the proportion of people living in households with income below a defined threshold or claiming benefits relating to low incomes. The indicators used for the income domain were:
  • Adults & children in income support households
  • Adults & children in pension credit households
  • Adults & children in income-based job seekers allowance households
  • Adults & children in tax credit (child tax credit and working tax credit) households below a low income threshold
  • National Asylum Support Service (NASS) supported asylum seekers in Wales in receipt of subsistence only and accommodation support

title: Employment score (Wales)
notes:
The purpose of this domain is to capture the extent of deprivation relating to employment at a small area level across Wales, and focuses on the proportion of working age people claiming out-of-work benefits. The indicators used for the employment domain were:
  • Claimants of unemployment-related benefits
  • Claimants of incapacity benefit/severe disablement allowance
  • Participants on New Deal for Young People and Intensive Activity Period (for New Deal 25+) not included in unemployment-related benefit counts
  • Participants on New Deal for Lone Parents

title: Health score (Wales)
notes:
The purpose of this domain is to capture the degree to which people are deprived of good health. The indicators used for the health domain were:
  • Limiting long-term illness (LLTI)
  • Standardised all-cause death rate
  • Standardised cancer incidence rate
  • Singleton low birth weights

title: Education score (Wales)
notes:
The purpose of this domain is to capture the extent of deprivation relating to education, training and skills at a small-area level across Wales. It is designed to reflect the 'stock' and 'flow' or educational disadvantage within an area, by capturing low attainment among children and young people and the lack of qualifications and skills in adults. The indicators used for the education domain were:
  • Key Stage 2, average point scores
  • Key Stage 3, average point scores
  • Key Stage 4, average point scores
  • Primary school absence rates
  • Secondary school absence rates
  • Proportion of people not entering Higher Education aged 18-19
  • Number of adults aged 25 - 59/64 with no qualifications

title: Access to services score (Wales)
notes:
The purpose of this domain is to illustrate the deprivation as a result of a household's inability to access a range of services, considered necessary for day-to-day living. The access is by walking or using public bus services or both. The indicators used for the geographical access to services domain were:
  • Food shop
  • GP surgery
  • Primary school
  • Post office
  • Public library
  • Leisure centre
  • NHS dentist
  • Secondary school
  • Transport nodes

title: Housing score (Wales)
notes:
The purpose of this domain is to capture deprivation though a lack of adequate housing. The indicators used for the housing domain were:
  • Lack of central heating
  • Overcrowding (excluding all student households)

title: Physical environment score (Wales)
notes:
The purpose of this domain is to measure environmental factors that may impact on quality of life in an area. Negative impacts on quality of life are judged to be a form of deprivation. Environmental deprivation is generally not correlated with social or economic deprivation in Wales. (ref: Walker et al 2003). This domain does not capture aspects of deprivation such as health inequalities (this is an objective of the Health domain). Data covering Wales is not available on actual impacts on quality of life; so factors were chosen that were judged to indicate an increased potential for reduced quality of life and had data available. The indicators used for the physical environment domain were:
  • Air Quality
  • Air Emissions
  • Flood risk
  • Proximity to waste disposal and industrial sites

title: Community safety score (Wales)
notes:
The purpose of this domain is to reflect where people are deprived of a safe community in which to live. Safety includes levels of household and personal crime and quality of experience in public places compatible with access to ordinary work, leisure and social relationships. The indicators used for the Community Safety domain were:
  • Police Force Recorded Crime
  • Youth Offenders
  • Adult Offenders
  • Fire Incidence

title: Index of Multiple Deprivation (Wales)
notes:
The Welsh Index of Multiple Deprivation 2008 is the official measure of deprivation for small areas in Wales. It was developed for the Welsh Assembly Government by the Assembly's Statistical Directorate and the Local Government Data Unit (Wales).

The WIMD 2008 is made up of eight separate domains (or kinds) of deprivation: income, employment, health, education, housing, environment, access to services, and community safety.

Each of them was based on a range of different indicators which meant that they were measured in different ways using different units. So before they could be combined the measurements had to be transformed to make them compatible. For example, if the height of something had been measured in metres and the weight in kilograms it would not make sense simply to add them together.

Income and employment were classed as the most important factors, and they were given the biggest weighting in the overall index. Although there is more to deprivation than poverty, not having enough money or a job is a big part of it.

title: Index of Multiple Deprivation (Scotland)
notes:
The Scottish Index of Multiple Deprivation (SIMD) 2009 identifies small area concentrations of multiple deprivation across Scotland in a consistent manner. The SIMD combines data from seven distinct domains or topic areas all of which are considered to be important contributors to deprivation levels. These domains have remained the same as in the previous version of the index, published in 2006, and the data used in compiling each one is the most appropriate and up to date that was available at the time of constructing the index.

The SIMD is a relative measure of deprivation that uses 6,505 data zones across Scotland as its unit of comparison. The rank applied to each of these data zones identifies each as being more or less deprived than all the others in the country. The rankings run from 1 being the most deprived to 6505 being the least deprived. Therefore the smaller the ranking the more deprived the data zone. As the SIMD is a relative measure it cannot show how much more deprived one data zone is than another, e.g. that a data zone ranked 5 is twice as deprived as a data zone ranked 10. In the same way the distance between each ranking can vary - so the gap between the data zones ranked 16 and 17 could be very small while the gap between those ranked 17 and 18 could be much bigger.

The SIMD can be used to identify the small areas with the highest concentrations of multiple deprivation in Scotland using either the overall index or the individual domains. The most commonly used cut off levels are 10%, 15% or 20% - although different cut offs may be required depending on individual policy or organisational focus.

title: Education score (Scotland)

title: Housing score (Scotland)
notes:

title: Access to services score (Scotland)

title: Antibody self-test kit device
notes:
Each participant of the Coronavirus Self-test Antibody Study received a self-administered lateral flow test through the post that was either a Fortress Fast COVID-19 Test or an AbC-19TM Rapid Test. Fortress kits produced results that differentiated between IgG antibodies (long-term) and IgM antibodies (short-term). AbC-19TM kits provided only positive test results for IgG antibodies.

~R4513~ and ~R4520~ show the technical specifications of the Fortress and AbC-19 test kits.

title: Antibody test result
notes:
Participants self-reported the result of their COVID-19 antibody self-testing device, either by submitting it online via their UK Biobank participant account, using a paper questionnaire returned to UK Biobank in the mail or via phone to the UK Biobank Participant Resource Centre. Fortress kits from Phase 1 produced results that differentiated between IgG antibodies (long-term) and IgM antibodies (short-term). AbC-19TM kits from Phase 2 provided test results for IgG antibodies only.

~R4500~ and ~R4501~ describe Phases 1 and 2 of the coronavirus self-test antibody study.

title: Date antibody test performed
notes: Participants reported the date that they completed their COVID-19 antibody home-testing device, either by submitting it via a web form, using a postal questionnaire, or, via an automated interactive voice response (IVR) call.

title: Received first COVID-19 vaccination
notes: When participants submitted their COVID-19 antibody test kit result they were asked - 'Have you received a first dose (jab) of a COVID-19 vaccine?'

title: Date of first COVID-19 vaccination
notes: When participants submitted their COVID-19 antibody test result, they were asked to "Please enter the date of your first vaccination" if they had responded with 'yes' to having received their first jab.

title: Received second COVID-19 vaccination
notes: When participants submitted their COVID-19 antibody test kit result they were asked - 'Have you received a second dose (jab) of a COVID-19 vaccine?'

title: Date of second COVID-19 vaccination
notes: When participants submitted their COVID-19 antibody test result, they were asked to "Please enter the date of your second vaccination" if they had responded with 'Yes' to having received their second jab.

title: When test result reported
notes:
The recorded date on which participants submitted their test results, either via web form or an automated interactive voice response (IVR) call.

Postal returns have no recorded date of submission as it was not possible to tell how long they had been in transfit and processing delays (e.g. weekends) meant that the data was not always transcribed electronically on the same day it arrived physically - such entries are flagged using ~C1642~.

title: Antibody test result
notes: Participants who accepted an invitation to the coronavirus infection study provided a blood sample using a Thriva coronavirus (COVID-19) antibody test kit. Blood samples were returned to a Thriva laboratory where they were analysed for N antibodies to SARS-CoV-2 using the Roche Elecsys Anti-SARS-CoV-2. The results were returned to UK Biobank.

title: Date antibody test sample analysed
notes: Participants returned their completed antibody test kit to a Thriva laboratory. This field records the date the result was obtained following analysis by the testing laboratory.

title: When antibody test sample received by laboratory
notes: Date antibody test sample received by laboratory performing the analysis.

title: Date antibody test kit despatched
notes: This is the date that the antibody test kit was physically despatched to a participant.

title: Antibody test result
notes: Participants took a blood sample using a microsampling finger-prick device, and returned the sample to the UK Biobank laboratory, where they were processed to separate the blood components. The plasma was then shipped to an external laboratory where assays were conducted for IgG antibodies to the spike (S) protein.

title: When antibody test sample received by laboratory
notes: The date the plasma sample was received at the external laboratory for assay testing.

title: Plate barcode
notes: This field indicates on which 384-well plate a particular sample was measured.

title: Well ID
notes: This field indicates the position within a plate of the well used to contain a particular participant's sample.

title: Date antibody test sample was analysed
notes: The date the ELISA test was run.

title: Date antibody test kit despatched
notes: The date that the antibody test kit was physically despatched to a participant.

title: Result pattern
notes: The pattern of results across all samples analysed. This field is provided as a string indicating the result of the test in order of instance, where 'P' represents a postive result, and 'N' represents a negative test result. The field is only populated for participants who returned two positive test results separated by one or more negative results, and is provided to flag participants who may have one or more false postive or false negative results.

title: Self-reported date that antibody test sample was collected
notes: The date the participant reported that they took the blood sample.

title: Date antibody test sample was received by UK Biobank
notes: The date the blood sample was received at the UK Biobank laboratory for initial processing.

title: Method of returning questionnaire results
notes: Method used to return results of the COVID-19 symptom questionnaire to UK Biobank.

title: When SARS-CoV-2 exposure questionnaire completed
notes: Date and time when online COVID-19 exposure questionnaire completed.

title: Antibody test result
notes:
Participants provided a blood sample using a Thriva coronavirus (COVID-19) antibody test kit, and returned it to the Pura Diagnostics laboratory where it was analysed for N antibodies to SARS-CoV-2 using the Roche Elecsys Anti-SARS-CoV-2. The results were returned to UK Biobank.

See ~R4496~ for the Overview document describing the coronavirus infection study.

title: Date antibody sample analysed
notes: Participants returned their completed antibody self-test sample to Pura Diagnostics laboratory (Thriva). This field records the date the result was obtained following analysis by the testing laboratory.

title: When antibody sample received

title: Date antibody test kit despatched

title: Self-reported date when antibody test sample was collected
notes: When participants were asked to complete the online symptom questionnaire they were asked to record the date on which they collected their self-test antibody kit sample.

title: Home location, east coordinate (1km resolution), wave 1
notes:
This location information is based on the postcode for the address the blood sampling kit was despatched to for wave 1.

The location co-ordinates use the Ordnance Survey (OSGB) reference, at a 1 kilometre resolution. This East co-ordinate needs to be used in conjunction with the North co-ordinate in ~F28171~.

For most purposes, grid co-ordinates rounded to a 1Km distance will provide sufficient information on location of residence at assessment. Research proposals that require location details to a finer level of granularity (i.e. 100m) should request ~F28172~ and ~F28173~, however special approval will be required to release the more detailed information.

title: Average retinal nerve fibre layer thickness (left)
notes: Average retinal nerve fibre layer (RNFL) thickness across all subfields in the left eye. The code used to generate the data in this field and the publication detailing the methods can be found in ~D1875~. Image source for measurements can be found in ~L100016~. Please be aware that these are the raw values generated by the Topcon Advanced Boundary Segmentation [TABS] software and should be quality controlled using the fields in ~L100116~.

title: Mental health conditions ever diagnosed by a professional
notes:
Mental Well-being online question:
"Have you been diagnosed with one or more of the following mental health conditions by a professional, even if you don't have it currently? By professional we mean any doctor, nurse or person with specialist training (such as a psychologist or therapist). Please include conditions even if you did not need treatment for them or if you did not agree with the diagnosis. Select all that apply."

Participants were offered 3 sets of options which have been combined here into a single answer.

The following conditions were in group A: Depression; Mania, hypomania, bipolar or manic-depression; Schizophrenia; Any other type of psychosis or psychotic illness; A personality disorder; Autism, Asperger's or autistic spectrum disorder; Attention deficit or attention deficit and hyperactivity disorder; Obsessive compulsive disorder (OCD)

The following conditions were in group B: Anxiety or nerves; Generalized anxiety disorder; Social anxiety or social phobia; Agoraphobia; Any other phobia (e.g. disabling fear of heights or spiders); Panic attacks; Panic disorder; Post traumatic stress disorder (PTSD)

The following conditions were in group C: Anorexia nervosa; Bulimia nervosa; Binge-eating disorder; Any other eating disorder

Select all that apply."

title: Carotid Artery Ultrasound (MAT format)
notes:
This field contains image files from the carotid ultrasound imaging.
These images are provided in .mat file format.

    Each .mat file contains the following:
  • CI_F - A 3-dimensional matrix of single precision values representing a 2-dimensional image through time.
  • FrameNum - The number of frames.
  • HP - Various meta-data describing the acquisition of the ultrasound image.
  • Xhv and Yhv: These variables may assist with coordinating plotting the image data. The values are calculated from the size of display area and sampling pitch. The image data at Fr frame: CI_F(Frame, i, j). Plot the value of CI_F(Fr, i, j) at the coordinate (Xhv(i), Yhv(j)).

Data have not been preprocessed and therefore, temporal and spatial filtering may be required to optimally utilise the images. UK Biobank cannot currently provide guidance on the best approach for these filterings.

Images in the original .Cine format, other images, and meta-data from the measurement device can be found in field 20241.

title: Haematocrit percentage
notes:
Result of "Haematocrit" assay, performed on blood sample, obtained from UK Biobank assessment centre visit. Haematocrit Percentage is the relative volume of packed erythrocytes to whole blood, computed by the formula: (red blood cells x mean corpuscular volume) / 10.

Analyser operating range was 0 to 99.9%

Typical reference range is 35.4 to 47.2%

title: Rate of ramp phase load increase (exercise test)
notes: The rate in watts per minute at which load increased during the ramp phase of an exercise test. If there was no ramp phase for a test, this value was set to 0.

title: Heart rate data used to estimate VO2max
notes: At various points during the exercise test, called trends, readings such as heart rate were recorded. In this field, trend refers to heart rate values computed automatically during these trends using a proprietary algorithm in the software (Cardiosoft). Alternatively heart rate can be computed from the raw ECG, referred to in this field as ECG. In some exercise tests, only trend data was available. ECG data were chosen preferentially over trend data when both data sources were available.

title: Estimation model used to compute VO2max
notes:
A multilevel framework was used to estimate VO2max. The framework contains 5 estimation models incorporating different phases of the exercise test: ramp, flat, and recovery phases.

See supplementary figure 12 and supplementary table 1 for an overview of how the models were assigned and the model equations in the associated paper:

Gonzales, T.I., Westgate, K., Strain, T. et al. Cardiorespiratory fitness assessment using risk-stratified exercise testing and dose-response relationships with disease outcomes. Sci Rep 11, 15315 (2021). DOI: 10.1038/s41598-021-94768-3

title: V02max per kg bodyweight estimated from the exercise test
notes:
VO2max per kg bodyweight estimated from heart rate response to low-risk personalised exercise tests.

The units of VO2max are milllilitres of oxygen used in one minute per kilogram of body weight.

title: Incidental finding report made during Abdominal MRI scan process
notes:
Indicates that an incidental finding report was made during the Abdominal MRI scan process.

This indicates an incidental finding, which is an observation flagged during the imaging visit (and not an actual finding) and which may or may not have any clinical significance or diagnostic relevance. For more information about how these have been generated please refer to ~R2068~.

title: Incidental finding report made during Ultrasound scan process
notes:
Indicates that an incidental finding report was made during the carotid ultrasound scan process.

This indicates an incidental finding, which is an observation flagged during the imaging visit (and not an actual finding) and which may or may not have any clinical significance or diagnostic relevance. For more information about how these have been generated please refer to ~R2068~.

Please note that incidental findings reporting only available for scans returned in DICOM format. Some imaging centres cannot return ultrasound scans in DICOM format, and thus incidental findings from ultrasound will not be reported across all centres. This field is therefore likely to contain incomplete data.

Immature Reticulocytes Fraction (Percentage) is an indication of new reticulocyte synthesis and is calculated from the reticulocytes (Percentage) as the total number of reticulocyte events in the outermost light scattering region, corresponding to immature reticulocytes, relative to the total number of reticulocytes and is reported as this ratio.

title: Immature reticulocyte fraction freeze-thaw cycles
notes: Number of freeze-thaw cycles sample went through before "Immature Reticulocytes Fraction" assay was performed (blood sample obtained from UK Biobank assessment centre visit).

title: Immature reticulocyte fraction acquisition time
notes: Original collection time of sample used for "Immature Reticulocytes Fraction" assay (blood sample obtained from UK Biobank assessment centre visit).

title: Immature reticulocyte fraction device ID
notes: Identifier for device used to measure Immature reticulocyte fraction

title: Immature reticulocyte fraction acquisition route
notes: Route whereby data for Immature reticulocyte fraction was transferred from analyser device to UK Biobank core LIMS database.

title: High light scatter reticulocyte percentage
notes: Result of "High Light Scatter Reticulocytes Percentage" assay, performed on blood sample, obtained from UK Biobank assessment centre visit. High Light Scatter Reticulocytes (Percentage) is computed as: (HLR / Total Erythrocytes) x 100.

title: High light scatter reticulocyte percentage freeze-thaw cycles
notes: Number of freeze-thaw cycles sample went through before "High Light Scatter Reticulocytes Percentage" assay was performed (blood sample obtained from UK Biobank assessment centre visit).

title: High light scatter reticulocyte percentage acquisition time
notes: Original collection time of sample used for "High Light Scatter Reticulocytes Percentage" assay (blood sample obtained from UK Biobank assessment centre visit).

title: High light scatter reticulocyte percentage device ID
notes: Identifier for device used to measure High light scatter reticulocyte percentage

title: High light scatter reticulocyte percentage acquisition route
notes: Route whereby data for High light scatter reticulocyte percentage was transferred from analyser device to UK Biobank core LIMS database.

title: High light scatter reticulocyte count
notes: Result of "High Light Scatter Reticulocytes Number" assay, performed on blood sample, obtained from UK Biobank assessment centre visit. High Light Scatter Reticulocytes Count is calculated as: (HLR / Total Erythrocytes) x red blood cells

title: High light scatter reticulocyte count freeze-thaw cycles
notes: Number of freeze-thaw cycles sample went through before "High Light Scatter Reticulocytes Number" assay was performed (blood sample obtained from UK Biobank assessment centre visit).

title: High light scatter reticulocyte count acquisition time
notes: Original collection time of sample used for "High Light Scatter Reticulocytes Number" assay (blood sample obtained from UK Biobank assessment centre visit).

title: High light scatter reticulocyte count device ID
notes: Identifier for device used to measure High light scatter reticulocyte count

title: High light scatter reticulocyte count acquisition route
notes: Route whereby data for High light scatter reticulocyte count was transferred from analyser device to UK Biobank core LIMS database.

title: Worked a non-standard shift schedule in the last month - version 1
notes:
Sleep online question: "In the past month, did you typically work a non-standard shift schedule?"

Here we define non-standard shift schedule as working hours outside the hours of 8am to 8pm.

This question was superseded on 10th February 2023 at 11am by the question in ~F30431~.

A screenshot of this question is not available as a resource.

title: Beta-globin Ct value in TaqMan assay (interim dataset)
notes: Ct (Cycle threshold) value of beta-globin in TaqMan assay.

title: U7 gene Ct value in TaqMan assay (interim dataset)
notes: Ct (Cycle threshold) value of U7 (U, viral unique region) gene in TaqMan assay.

title: DR1 gene Ct value in TaqMan assay (interim dataset)
notes: Ct (Cycle threshold) value of DR1 (DR, viral direct repeat, 2 per genome) gene in TaqMan assay.

title: TaqMan assay screen result (interim dataset)
notes:
Results of TaqMan PCR based on Delta Ct values of the U7 and the DR1 genes and beta-globin Ct such as:
Delta U7 Ct = beta-globin Ct - U7 Ct (Derived from ~F30586~ and ~F30587~)
Delta DR1 Ct = beta-globin Ct - DR1 Ct (Derived from ~F30586~ and ~F30588~)

title: Tractography endpoints coordinates
notes: Contains the tractography endpoint coordinates for all streamlines. This facilitates assignment of pre-generated streamlines to any parcellation of interest. This file is stored in a half-precision floating-point format (16 bits) to reduce storage requirements with minimal loss of precision.

title: Tractography quality metrics
notes: Contains the sampled (per streamline) metrics (length, sift2 weights, and mean microstructural properties) for all streamlines. These are also stored in half-precision floating-point format, with multiplicative factors of 1e3 and 1e-3 applied to the mean MD and mean S0 metrics, respectively, to scale the magnitudes of floating-point values toward unity and therefore mitigate loss of precision.

notes:
For the pilot batch 1, samples were arranged in different well locations for the different assays, and field 31047 indicates both locations. For all other batches the well locations were the same for the different assays.

title: Sample analysis well
notes:
For the pilot batch 1, samples were arranged in different well locations for the different assays. For all other batches the well locations were the same for the different assays. This field indicates well location for each assay for all batches.

This field is arrayed to indicate the well position for each assay.
Array index = 0 - 4plex assay well position - relating to ~F31040~, ~F31041~, ~F31042~, and ~F31043~.
Array index = 1 - ptau assay well position - relating to ~F31044~.

These data were derived in association with project 76059.

title: Comment code pTau sample state
notes:
Amyloid beta-40, Amyloid beta-42, Glial fibrillary acidic protein and NeuroFilament Light were assayed on a Quanterix Simoa HD-X platform employing a 4plex E assay. A separate Simoa assay was performed for pTau-181.

For the pilot plate 1, samples were arranged in different well locations for the different assays, and field 31047 indicates both locations. For all other plates the well locations were the same for the different assays.

Field 31048 indicates plex samples with known issues. Where there is no comment flag it means that no issues were detected during plex processing, but data should still be checked for quality before use.

These data were derived in association with project 76059.

title: Comment code plex sample state
notes:
Amyloid beta-40, Amyloid beta-42, Glial fibrillary acidic protein and NeuroFilament Light were assayed on a Quanterix Simoa HD-X platform employing a 4plex E assay. A separate Simoa assay was performed for pTau-181.

For the pilot plate 1, samples were arranged in different well locations for the different assays, and field 31047 indicates both locations. For all other plates the well locations were the same for the different assays.

Field 31048 indicates plex samples with known issues. Where there is no comment flag it means that no issues were detected during plex processing, but data should still be checked for quality before use.

These data were derived in association with project 76059.

title: Middle slice QC score
notes:
Quality control (QC) score for middle slice.

QC score 2 = sub-optimal quality but analysable and/or slice acquired too high or low
QC score 3 = poor quality/not analysable

title: Basal slice QC score
notes:
Quality control (QC) score for basal slice.

QC score 2 = sub-optimal quality but analysable and/or left ventricular outflow tract (LVOT) appears in systole but is <25% of the circumference in the basal slice
QC score 3 = poor quality/not analysable or LVOT appears in diastole or >25% of the circumference in systole in the basal slice

title: Apical slice QC score
notes:
Quality control (QC) score for apical slice.

QC score 2 = sub-optimal quality but analysable
QC score 3 = poor quality/not analysable or apical slice is too low (no blood pool seen)

title: Torsion QC score
notes:
Quality control (QC) score for torsion.

QC score 2 = sub-optimal quality but analysable with torsion derived using basal and apical slices
QC score 3 = poor quality/not analysable
QC score 4 = sub-optimal quality but analysable with torsion derived using basal and middle slices
QC score 5 = sub-optimal quality but analysable with torsion derived using middle and apical slices

title: End systolic circumferential strain (mid)

title: End systolic circumferential strain (apex)

title: End systolic torsion

title: End systolic torsion rate

title: Records in COVID-19 vaccination dataset
notes:
Add this field to a basket to gain access to ~T800~ (covid19_vaccination) on the Data Portal. If included, the field will also appear in a main UK Biobank dataset where it will give a count of the number of rows for each participant in this table.

Please note that this data is only available for research related to COVID-19; principal investigators must contact the Access Management Team to request authorisation to access the data.

title: When COVID19 vaccinations administered
notes:
Note that, in the covid19_vaccination Data Portal table from which these data are derived, there are a small number of participants with multiple vaccination records on the same date. For this summary field, these records have been condensed into single instances per date and participant.

Please note that this field is only available for research related to COVID-19; principal investigators must contact the Access Management Team to request authorisation to access the data.

title: Release tranche
notes: The WES data was released in a serious of batches/tranches over time in order to facilitate early access by researchers as it was generated over a period of years. This field indicates within which tranche the data for any particular participant first appeared.

title: Sequencing Provider
notes: Sequencing provider for each sample in the WGS project.

title: Sample plate ID
notes: Sequencing provider plate barcode. A 10 digit alphanumeric EAN13 standard GS1 type linear barcode format orientated on the long side of the plate.

title: Shipment batch number
notes: Numerical shipment identifier. Batch numbers increase consecutively from Batch 1 for each sequencing provider.

title: Sample quant reading (UKB)
notes: Sample concentration of normalised sample as measured by UKB.

title: Sample quant reading (sequence provider)
notes: Sample concentration as measured by sequencing providers.

title: Library prep plate barcode
notes: Barcode of SBS format plate used during library preparation.

title: Library prep plate position (well)
notes: Row and column position on library plate, e.g. A01

title: Yield
notes: Sequence data quantity

title: Proportion of mapped read pairs
notes: Percentage of mapped read-pairs with appropriate orientation and separation. Threshold is >=95% of the total mapped reads

title: Coverage
notes: Percentage of autosome sequenced to >=15X

title: Average batch coverage
notes: The mean sample genome coverage across the montly sequencing batch to deliver 95% of the autosome covered to >=15X, is expected to be approximately 30X across the genome with a min coverage of 26X

title: Freemix verify BAM ID
notes: Freemix percentage value of sample contamination levels

title: NRD genotyping
notes: Sample discordance levels at non-reference genotypes.

title: Quality requirements achieved
notes: Pass/fail flag indicating whether generated sequence data has met all quality thresholds.

title: Read haps
notes: Read haps estimation of contamination. This is mandatory for contamination failed samples but optional for passed samples.

title: GraphTyper population level WGS variants, BGEN format [500k release]
notes: Joint call BGEN files based on 500K whole genome sequencing resource generated by DECODE

title: Date of cancer diagnosis
notes:
Date of cancer diagnosis, acquired from central registry.

Note that data from the most recent 12-18 months is still accruing (i.e. it is not complete).

The events/dates are indexed in the order in which they are received and processed by UK Biobank rather than in their own chronological order.

title: Type of cancer: ICD10
notes:
The ICD-10 code for the type of cancer.

Acquired from central registry.

The ICD-10 tree displayed on this page includes all cancer records for each UK Biobank participant (for which there may be multiple ICD codes). For more information on the first diagnosed cancer in each participant, please refer to ~L100092~.

title: Age at death
notes: Age calculated as interval between Date of Birth and Death.

title: Age at cancer diagnosis
notes: Age calculated as interval between Dates of Birth and Cancer diagnosis.

title: Reported occurrences of cancer
notes:
This is the number of reports of cancer received from UK National registries. Participants who have never been reported as having cancer do not contribute to this field unless a report was received then subsequently withdrawn.

Please note that this field represents simply the number of cancer records per participant; due to probable (pseudo)duplicates between different sources these counts likely do not accurately reflect the number of unique cancer diagnoses. Please see ~R115558~ for further details.

The counts indicate records where there is a non-missing date of diagnosis; a record will be counted even where other diagnosis information such as site and/or morphology are missing or invalid.

title: Description of cause of death
notes:
Underlying/primary cause of death reported for participant - text description. This is the cause of death (entered as free-text) from the Medical Certificate of Cause of Death (MCCD). The data-field reveals the sequence leading to death, underlying cause and contributory causes that led to subsequent death. It is composed of the following sections:
  • I(a) is free-text description stored in the I(a) section on the death certificate;
  • I(b) is free-text description stored in the I(b) section on the death certificate;
  • I(c) is free-text description stored in the I(c) section on the death certificate;
  • I(d) is free-text description stored in the I(d) section on the death certificate (populated for Scottish deaths only);
  • II is free-text description stored in the II section on the death certificate;
  • Verdict given (where present) - information from post mortem investigation and/or results of investigations initiated ante mortem.

Note that this may not match the coded values in ~F40001~ and ~F40002~ due to transcription errors at source. The content has also been manually cleaned to remove any information which might be used towards identifying the subject.

title: Histology of cancer tumour
notes:
This is a numeric code relating to the histology of the tumour, provided by the cancer registry. It should be interpreted in combination with ~F40012~ (tumour behaviour code); together these comprise the ICD-O-3 morphology code.

Previously an encoding was derived for histology codes; however given that these must be interpreted alongside the behaviour codes and standard definitions are not available for all combinations, the Showcase encoding has been deprecated. Please refer to the WHO downloads area (requires an account) for a current version of the ICD-O-3 classification. ICD-O-3 morphology codes are also detailed in ~R126048~.

For more information about cancer registry data, please see ~R115558~.

title: Behaviour of cancer tumour
notes:
This is a numeric code relating to the behaviour of the tumour, provided by the cancer registry. It should be interpreted in combination with ~F40011~ (tumour histology code); together these comprise the ICD-O-3 morphology code.

Previously an encoding was derived for behaviour codes; however given that these must be interpreted alongside the histology codes and standard definitions are not available for all combinations, the Showcase encoding has been deprecated. Please refer to the WHO downloads area (requires an account) for a current version of the ICD-O-3 classification. ICD-O-3 morphology codes are also detailed in ~R126048~.

For more information about cancer registry data, please see ~R115558~.

title: Inpatient record origin
notes:
Indicates the origin of the data in which the original hospital inpatient record was supplied to UK Biobank.

This field corresponds to the field DSOURCE on the HESIN table; see the Inpatient Data Dictionary (~R141140~) in ~L2000~ for information about the HESIN table.

In order to conduct detailed analyses of this data using the source information, researchers will need to gain access to the HESIN table by adding ~F41259~ to their basket.

title: Records in death dataset
notes:
Adding this field to a basket will grant access to the DEATH and DEATH_CAUSE tables on the Data Portal. The DEATH table replicates the information in ~F40000~, ~F40018~ and ~F40020~. The DEATH_CAUSE table replicates the information in ~F40001~ and ~F40002~. See ~R115559~ for additional information.

If included, the field will also appear in a main UK Biobank dataset where it will give a count of the number of rows for each participant in the DEATH table.

title: Sleep - Day hour average
notes: The average proportion of time spent sleeping per hour across all days. The data is stored as 24 comma seperated values, each representing an hour of the day, starting with 12am and ending with 11pm. Please use the fields in ~L1011~ to quality control participants for completeness of the accelerometry recording period and the related data fields for the corresponding proportion for the other activity levels. Where data was missing for a participant, the value was imputed from the available data as outlined in ~D2040~. Please see ~P5649~ for more details.

title: Liver iron (Fe)
notes:
Liver iron (Fe) derived from liver MRI scan.

Derived variable provided by Perspectum (application #9914). See the following publication:

Parisinos CA, Wilman HR, Thomas EL, et al. (2020) Genome-wide and Mendelian randomisation studies of liver MRI yield insights into the pathogenesis of steatohepatitis. J Hepatol. 73(2):241-251. doi: 10.1016/j.jhep.2020.03.032

title: Proton density fat fraction (PDFF)
notes:
Liver fat percentage is defined as : fat / ( water + fat )

Derived variable provided by Perspectum (application #9914). See the following publications:

Wilman HR, Kelly M, Garratt S, et al. (2017) Characterisation of liver fat in the UK Biobank cohort. PLoS ONE 12(2): e0172921. doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0172921

Parisinos CA, Wilman HR, Thomas EL, et al. (2020) Genome-wide and Mendelian randomisation studies of liver MRI yield insights into the pathogenesis of steatohepatitis. J Hepatol. 73(2):241-251. doi: 10.1016/j.jhep.2020.03.032

title: Liver iron corrected T1 (ct1)
notes:
Liver iron corrected T1 (ct1) is measure of liver inflammation and fibrosis.

Derived variable provided by Perspectum (application #9914) See the following publications:

Mojtahed A, Kelly CJ, Herlihy AH, et al. (2019) Reference range of liver corrected T1 values in a population at low risk for fatty liver disease-a UK Biobank sub-study, with an appendix of interesting cases. Abdom Radiol (NY). 44(1):72-84. doi: 10.1007/s00261-018-1701-2

Parisinos CA, Wilman HR, Thomas EL, et al. (2020) Genome-wide and Mendelian randomisation studies of liver MRI yield insights into the pathogenesis of steatohepatitis. J Hepatol. 73(2):241-251. doi: 10.1016/j.jhep.2020.03.032

title: Acquisition protocol
notes:
Acquisition protocol used to capture liver MRI images.

This data field gives the acquisition protocol used to capture liver MRI images as part of the analysis of ~F40060~, ~F40061~ and ~F40062~ in ~L126~ (Liver MRI).

Between 7 July 2016 and 30 October 2016 there was a gradual replacement of bulk data field 20203 "Liver imaging - gradient echo - DICOM" with bulk data field 20254 "Liver imaging - IDEAL protocol - DICOM". Both of these acquisitions are multi-echo gradient echo sequences from which measures of liver fat and liver iron can be derived. Due to this change in imaging protocol there may be systematic differences in derived measures which researchers may wish to take into account when relating to other measures.

"Proton density fat fraction (PDFF)" (~F40061~) is produced from analysis of either "Liver imaging - gradient echo - DICOM" (~F20203~) or "Liver imaging - IDEAL protocol - DICOM" (~F20254~).

"Liver iron (Fe)" (~F40060~) is produced from analysis of either "Liver imaging - gradient echo - DICOM" (~F20203~) or "Liver imaging - IDEAL protocol - DICOM" (~F20254~).

"Liver iron corrected T1 (ct1)" (~F40062~) is produced from analysis of "Liver Imaging - T1 ShMoLLI - DICOM" (~F20204~) and either "Liver imaging - gradient echo - DICOM" (~F20203~) or "Liver imaging - IDEAL protocol - DICOM" (~F20254~).

title: Records of COVID-19 test results
notes:
Adding this field to a basket will grant access to the covid19_result_england, covid19_result_scotland and covid19_result_wales tables on the Data Portal. If included, the field will also appear in a main UK Biobank dataset where it will give a count of the number of rows for each participant across these three tables.

This field will also grant access to table covid19_misc in the Data Portal. This table gives participants' blood group extracted from imputed genotyped data (~F23165~) and was added in July 2020 as a result of the suggestion that blood group may affect COVID-19 outcomes.

Details of the structure of the above tables as well as the meaning of the encoded values used can be found by downloading the Covid-19 test result data dictionary. Note that in July 2023 the structure of the covid19_result_scotland table was altered following a change to the database that Scottish COVID-19 test results are extracted from by the data provider.

More details on linkage of microbiological samples to the UK Biobank are available at ~Ehttp://www.bugbank.uk/~. Please also see ~R1758~ for more detail about the PHE linkage for the English data.

Please note that prior to 6th July 2021, a small proportion (6.5%) of the records in the covid19_result_scotland table related to lateral flow device testing. These records have been removed and all data in this table now relate to PCR testing. In addition, some issues with linkage that affected 1.4% of records in the covid19_result_england table were identified, and these records were removed in early March 2023.

title: Volume of DNA held by UKB
notes: Volume held of "DNA" sample, derived from UK Biobank assessment centre visits.

title: Case-control status for COVID19 imaging repeat
notes:
Provides a numeric value for every participant who has attended a repeat imaging appointment as part of the COVID-19 re-imaging study. The value comprises a unique identifier assigned to each case-control set followed by the last digit denoting the case-control status of that individual, where 0 is a control and 1 is a case.

All Covid19 repeat imaging data is released under instance 3.

For more information on this field and the study eligibility and case-control matching see the Resource.

title: Source of positive COVID test result
notes: Provides the diagnostic source of COVID-19 cases in the COVID-19 re-imaging study. We receive data from multiple sources on whether a participant has been diagnosed with COVID-19, comprising PCR test results, hospital inpatient admissions and GP records. Participants were also invited to undertake a home-based lateral flow test (LFT) to identify antibodies to SARS-CoV-2 infection and those who had antibodies from the virus were eligible as cases. Many participants have more than one diagnostic source.

Number of weeks of gestation is based on the World Health Organisation (WHO) definition, which specifies the time from the last menstrual period up until birth.

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

Episode status identifies whether the episode has finished before the end of the HES data year (31 March) or if the patient is still under a period of care.

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

Note that the original information was obtained from a variety of external sources, some of which used overlapping and contradictory coding schemes. The values in this field can therefore only be interpreted when the source of each item is known (see ~F41252~) using the source-specific codings ~C202~, ~C241~, ~C242~ and ~C252~. It is recommended that the re-coded ~F41236~ is used instead of this one.
