title: Episodes containing "Destination on discharge from hospital" data (polymorphic)
notes:
This field indicates (for each participant) the number of in-patient Health Episode Statistics (HES) records in the UKB repository which contain "Destination on discharge from hospital" information. Participants with zero records are not itemised.

Destination on discharge identifies whether a patient was due to return to their usual place of residence on leaving hospital, or whether they were due to go elsewhere.

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

Note that the original information was obtained from a variety of external sources, some of which used overlapping and contradictory coding schemes. The values in this field can therefore only be interpreted when the source of each item is known (see ~F41252~) using the source-specific codings ~C205~, ~C247~ and ~C255~. It is recommended that the re-coded ~F41248~ is used instead of this one.

title: Episodes containing "External cause - ICD10" data
notes:
This field indicates (for each participant) the number of in-patient Health Episode Statistics (HES) records in the UKB repository which contain "External cause - ICD10" information. Participants with zero records are not itemised.

An external cause is an environmental event causing injury, poisoning or other type of adverse effect. External causes are coded according to the International Classification of Diseases version-10 (ICD10).

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

title: Episodes containing "External cause - ICD10 addendum" data
notes:
This field indicates (for each participant) the number of in-patient Health Episode Statistics (HES) records in the UKB repository which contain "External cause - ICD10 addendum" information. Participants with zero records are not itemised.

Addendum data consists of special characters affixed to the ICD code, encoded with ~C41~.

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

title: Episodes containing "Operation status" data
notes:
This field indicates (for each participant) the number of in-patient Health Episode Statistics (HES) records in the UKB repository which contain "Operation status" information. Participants with zero records are not itemised.

This field indicates whether an operative procedure was carried out during the episode or not.

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

title: Episodes containing "Duration of post-operative stay" data
notes:
This field indicates (for each participant) the number of in-patient Health Episode Statistics (HES) records in the UKB repository which contain "Duration of post-operative stay" information. Participants with zero records are not itemised.

This is the time between the operation being carried out and the end date of the episode.

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

title: Episodes containing "Duration of pre-operative stay" data
notes:
This field indicates (for each participant) the number of in-patient Health Episode Statistics (HES) records in the UKB repository which contain "Duration of pre-operative stay" information. Participants with zero records are not itemised.

This is the time between the episode start date and the date at which the operation was carried out.

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

title: Episodes containing "Patient classification on admission" data (polymorphic)
notes:
This field indicates (for each participant) the number of in-patient Health Episode Statistics (HES) records in the UKB repository which contain "Patient classification on admission" information. Participants with zero records are not itemised.

Patient classification on admission identifies the type of patient, e.g. whether they are a regular attender or a maternity admission, etc.

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

Note that the original information was obtained from a variety of external sources, some of which used overlapping and contradictory coding schemes. The values in this field can therefore only be interpreted when the source of each item is known (see ~F41252~) using the source-specific codings ~C208~, ~C245~, ~C246~ and ~C254~. It is recommended that the re-coded ~F41240~ is used instead of this one.

title: Episodes containing "Intended management of patient" data (polymorphic)
notes:
This field indicates (for each participant) the number of in-patient Health Episode Statistics (HES) records in the UKB repository which contain "Intended management of patient" information. Participants with zero records are not itemised.

The intended management of a patient is their planned duration of hospital stay, i.e. whether an overnight stay was anticipated or not.

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

Note that the original information was obtained from a variety of external sources, some of which used overlapping and contradictory coding schemes. The values in this field can therefore only be interpreted when the source of each item is known (see ~F41252~) using the source-specific codings ~C209~ and ~C260~. It is recommended that the re-coded ~F41241~ is used instead of this one.

title: Episodes containing "Main speciality of consultant" data (polymorphic)
notes:
This field indicates (for each participant) the number of in-patient Health Episode Statistics (HES) records in the UKB repository which contain "Main speciality of consultant" information. Participants with zero records are not itemised.

The main speciality of the consultant is specialism under which the consultant is contracted e.g. cardiology or geriatric medicine, etc.

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

Note that the original information was obtained from a variety of external sources, some of which used overlapping and contradictory coding schemes. The values in this field can therefore only be interpreted when the source of each item is known (see ~F41252~) using the source-specific codings ~C210~ and ~C258~. It is recommended that the re-coded ~F41242~ is used instead of this one.

title: Episodes containing "Treatment speciality of consultant" data (polymorphic)
notes:
This field indicates (for each participant) the number of in-patient Health Episode Statistics (HES) records in the UKB repository which contain "Treatment speciality of consultant" information. Participants with zero records are not itemised.

The treatment speciality of the consultant is specialism under which the consultant was working e.g. cardiology or geriatric medicine, etc.

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

Note that the original information was obtained from a variety of external sources, some of which used overlapping and contradictory coding schemes. The values in this field can therefore only be interpreted when the source of each item is known (see ~F41252~) using the source-specific codings ~C211~, ~C250~, ~C251~ and ~C257~. It is recommended that the re-coded ~F41243~ is used instead of this one.

title: Episodes containing "Date of first antenatal assessment" data
notes:
This field indicates (for each participant) the number of in-patient Health Episode Statistics (HES) records in the UKB repository which contain "Date of first antenatal assessment" information. Participants with zero records are not itemised.

Date of first antenatal assessment is the date when the pregnancy was first assessed and arrangements for antenatal care were made.

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

title: Episodes containing "Gestation period at first antenatal assessment" data
notes:
This field indicates (for each participant) the number of in-patient Health Episode Statistics (HES) records in the UKB repository which contain "Gestation period at first antenatal assessment" information. Participants with zero records are not itemised.

Gestation period at first antenatal assessment is the time from the last menstrual period to the date when the pregnancy was first assessed.

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

title: Episodes containing "Antenatal stay" data
notes:
This field indicates (for each participant) the number of in-patient Health Episode Statistics (HES) records in the UKB repository which contain "Antenatal stay" information. Participants with zero records are not itemised.

Antenatal stay is the number of days between the start of the maternity episode and the delivery of the first baby.

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

title: Episodes containing "Intended delivery place" data
notes:
This field indicates (for each participant) the number of in-patient Health Episode Statistics (HES) records in the UKB repository which contain "Intended delivery place" information. Participants with zero records are not itemised.

Intended delivery place identifies where the birth was planned to take place.

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

title: Episodes containing "Reason for changing delivery place" data
notes:
This field indicates (for each participant) the number of in-patient Health Episode Statistics (HES) records in the UKB repository which contain "Reason for changing delivery place" information. Participants with zero records are not itemised.

Reason for changing delivery place identifies whether a change in where the birth took place was due to clinical or other matters.

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

title: Episodes containing "Anaesthetic administered during delivery" data
notes:
This field indicates (for each participant) the number of in-patient Health Episode Statistics (HES) records in the UKB repository which contain "Anaesthetic administered during delivery" information. Participants with zero records are not itemised.

This field identifies, for example, whether a general anaesthetic or an epidural was administered either before or during labour.

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

title: Episodes containing "Anaesthetic administered post delivery" data
notes:
This field indicates (for each participant) the number of in-patient Health Episode Statistics (HES) records in the UKB repository which contain "Anaesthetic delivered post delivery" information. Participants with zero records are not itemised.

This field identifies, for example, whether a general anaesthetic or an epidural was administered after labour.

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

title: Episodes containing "Delivery onset method" data
notes:
This field indicates (for each participant) the number of in-patient Health Episode Statistics (HES) records in the UKB repository which contain "Delivery onset method" information. Participants with zero records are not itemised.

Delivery onset method identifies whether the onset of labour was spontaneous or clinically induced.

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

title: Episodes containing "Number of babies delivered from single pregnancy" data
notes:
This field indicates (for each participant) the number of in-patient Health Episode Statistics (HES) records in the UKB repository which contain "Number of babies delivered from single pregnancy" information. Participants with zero records are not itemised.

This is the number of babies delivered from a single pregnancy and includes both live and stillborn babies.

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

title: Episodes containing "Postnatal stay" data
notes:
This field indicates (for each participant) the number of in-patient Health Episode Statistics (HES) records in the UKB repository which contain "Postnatal stay" information. Participants with zero records are not itemised.

Postnatal stay is the number of days between the birth of the baby and the episode end date.

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

title: Episodes containing "Level of neonatal care" data
notes:
This field indicates (for each participant) the number of in-patient Health Episode Statistics (HES) records in the UKB repository which contain "Level of neonatal care" information. Participants with zero records are not itemised.

Level of neonatal care identifies whether the new born baby was given normal care or required special or intensive care.

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

title: Episodes containing "Mother age on date of delivery" data
notes:
This field indicates (for each participant) the number of in-patient Health Episode Statistics (HES) records in the UKB repository which contain "Mother age on date of delivery" information. Participants with zero records are not itemised.

This field contains the mothers age on the date of delivery. This is calculated from the mother's date of birth and the birth date of the first baby.

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

title: Episodes containing "Number of previous pregnancies" data
notes:
This field indicates (for each participant) the number of in-patient Health Episode Statistics (HES) records in the UKB repository which contain "Number of previous pregnancies" information. Participants with zero records are not itemised.

This field contains the number of previous pregnancies, which includes all previous pregnancies which resulted in a registerable birth.

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

title: Episodes containing "Carer support indicator" data
notes:
This field indicates (for each participant) the number of in-patient Health Episode Statistics (HES) records in the UKB repository which contain "Carer support indicator" information. Participants with zero records are not itemised.

Carer support indicator identifies whether a carer is available to the patient at their usual place of residence.

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

title: Episodes containing "Detention date" data
notes:
This field indicates (for each participant) the number of in-patient Health Episode Statistics (HES) records in the UKB repository which contain "Detention date" information. Participants with zero records are not itemised.

This is the date when the person was first detained in the current continuous period of detention.

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

title: Episodes containing "Detention category" data
notes:
This field indicates (for each participant) the number of in-patient Health Episode Statistics (HES) records in the UKB repository which contain "Detention category" information. Participants with zero records are not itemised.

Detention category identifies the legislation under which the person was detained.

This information is not present in HES records dated after 2001.

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

title: Episodes containing "Mental category of patient" data
notes:
This field indicates (for each participant) the number of in-patient Health Episode Statistics (HES) records in the UKB repository which contain "Mental category of patient" information. Participants with zero records are not itemised.

The mental categories are in accordance with the Mental Health Act 1983.

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

title: Episodes containing "History of psychiatric care on admission" data
notes:
This field indicates (for each participant) the number of in-patient Health Episode Statistics (HES) records in the UKB repository which contain "History of psychiatric care on admission" information. Participants with zero records are not itemised.

History of psychiatric care identifies whether a patient has previously had a psychiatric episode in hospital or not.

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

title: Episodes containing "Legal status of patient" data
notes:
This field indicates (for each participant) the number of in-patient Health Episode Statistics (HES) records in the UKB repository which contain "Legal status of patient" information. Participants with zero records are not itemised.

Legal status determines whether the person was formally or informally detained at the date of psychiatric census.

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

title: Episodes containing "Episode type" data
notes:
This field indicates (for each participant) the number of in-patient Health Episode Statistics (HES) records in the UKB repository which contain "Episode type" information. Participants with zero records are not itemised.

Episode type identifies whether the period of care in hospital was a general episode or (for example) a psychiatric episode.

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

title: Episodes containing "Diagnoses - main ICD10" data
notes:
This field indicates (for each participant) the number of in-patient Health Episode Statistics (HES) records in the UKB repository which contain "Diagnoses - main ICD10" information. Participants with zero records are not itemised.

Diagnoses are coded according to the International Classification of Diseases version-10 (ICD10).

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

title: Episodes containing "Diagnoses - main ICD10 - addendum" data
notes:
This field indicates (for each participant) the number of in-patient Health Episode Statistics (HES) records in the UKB repository which contain "Diagnoses - main ICD10 - addendum" information. Participants with zero records are not itemised.

Addendum data consists of special characters affixed to the ICD code, encoded with ~C41~.

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

title: Episodes containing "Diagnoses - main ICD9" data
notes:
This field indicates (for each participant) the number of in-patient Health Episode Statistics (HES) records in the UKB repository which contain "Diagnoses - main ICD9" information. Participants with zero records are not itemised.

Diagnoses are coded according to the International Classification of Diseases version-9 (ICD9).

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

title: Episodes containing "Diagnoses - main ICD9 - addendum" data
notes:
This field indicates (for each participant) the number of in-patient Health Episode Statistics (HES) records in the UKB repository which contain "Diagnoses - main ICD9 - addendum" information. Participants with zero records are not itemised.

Addendum are special characters or local codes which have been affixed to the ICD code, but do not have universal definition. They have been preserved to reflect the true state of the data.

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

title: Episodes containing "Operative procedure - main OPCS4" data
notes:
This field indicates (for each participant) the number of in-patient Health Episode Statistics (HES) records in the UKB repository which contain "Operative procedure - main OPCS" information. Participants with zero records are not itemised.

Operative procedures are coded according to the Office of Population Censuses and Surveys Classification of Interventions and Procedures, version 4 (OPCS-4).

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

title: Episodes containing "Operative procedure - main OPCS4 - addendum" data
notes:
This field indicates (for each participant) the number of in-patient Health Episode Statistics (HES) records in the UKB repository which contain "Operative procedure - main OPCS - addendum" information. Participants with zero records are not itemised.

Addendum are special characters or local codes which have been affixed to the OPCS code, but do not have a universal definition. They have been preserved to reflect the true state of the data.

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

title: Episodes containing "Date of operation" data
notes:
This field indicates (for each participant) the number of in-patient Health Episode Statistics (HES) records in the UKB repository which contain "Date of operation" information. Participants with zero records are not itemised.

This date corresponds to the main operation only. (For secondary operations and procedures, see ~F41082~ - Episodes containing "Dates of operations" data.)

In order to conduct analyses using this information, researchers must include this data-field in their application, however access will be given in-situ rather than as a download.

title: Records in HES inpatient operations dataset
notes:
Adding this field to a basket will grant access to the HESIN_OPER table on the Data Portal. See the Inpatient Data Dictionary (~R141140~) in ~L2000~ for information about the HESIN_OPER table.

If included, the field will also appear in a main UK Biobank dataset where it will give a count of the number of rows for each participant in the HESIN_OPER table.

title: Detention categories (recoded)
notes:
This field is a summary of the distinct detention category codes a participant has had recorded in their hospital inpatient records. The detention category identifies the legislation under which the person was detained.

Note that the original information was obtained from a variety of external sources, some of which used overlapping and contradictory coding schemes. This field has been re-coded to remove such data conflicts, using a code mapping available in ~R146641~.

This field corresponds to the field DETNCAT_UNI on the HESIN_PSYCH table; see the Inpatient Data Dictionary (~R141140~) in ~L2000~ for information about the HESIN_PSYCH table.

In order to conduct detailed analyses of this data using the source information, researchers will need to gain access to the HESIN_PSYCH and HESIN tables by adding ~F41289~ and ~F41259~ to their basket.

title: History of psychiatric care on admission (recoded)
notes:
This field is a summary of the distinct history of psychiatric care codes a participant has had recorded in their hospital inpatient records. History of psychiatric care identifies whether a patient has previously had a psychiatric episode in hospital or not.

Note that the original information was obtained from a variety of external sources, some of which used overlapping and contradictory coding schemes. This field has been re-coded to remove such data conflicts, using a code mapping available in ~R146641~.

This field corresponds to the field ADMISTAT_UNI on the HESIN_PSYCH table; see the Inpatient Data Dictionary (~R141140~) in ~L2000~ for information about the HESIN_PSYCH table.

In order to conduct detailed analyses of this data using the source information, researchers will need to gain access to the HESIN_PSYCH and HESIN tables by adding ~F41289~ and ~F41259~ to their basket.

title: Operative procedures - main OPCS4
notes:
This field is a summary of the main operation and procedure codes a participant has had recorded across all their hospital inpatient records. Operative procedures are coded according to the Office of Population Censuses and Surveys Classification of Interventions and Procedures, version 4 (OPCS-4).

The corresponding date when each main procedure was first recorded in the inpatient data can be found in ~F41260~.

title: External causes - ICD10
notes:
This field is a summary of the distinct external cause codes a participant has had recorded across all their episodes in hospital. An external cause is an environmental event causing injury, poisoning or other type of adverse effect. External causes are coded according to the International Classification of Diseases version-10 (ICD-10).

In the record-level hospital inpatient data the external cause codes appear in the DIAG_ICD10 field of the HESIN_DIAG table with LEVEL=3.

In order to conduct detailed analyses of the data using the source information, researchers will need to gain access to the HESIN_DIAG and HESIN tables by adding ~F41234~ and ~F41259~ to their basket.

title: Diagnoses - main ICD10
notes:
This field is a summary of the distinct primary/main diagnosis codes a participant has had recorded across all their hospital inpatient records. Diagnoses are coded according to the International Classification of Diseases version-10 (ICD-10).

The corresponding date each diagnosis code was first recorded in the inpatient data as the primary/main diagnosis can be found in data-field ~F41262~.

title: Diagnoses - main ICD9
notes:
This field is a summary of the distinct primary/main diagnosis codes a participant has had recorded across all their hospital inpatient records. Diagnoses are coded according to the International Classification of Diseases version-9 (ICD-9).

The corresponding date each primary/main diagnosis code was first recorded in each participant's hospital inpatient records is given in ~F41263~.

Please note ICD-9 coded hospital inpatient data are only available for older Scottish hospital records.

title: Diagnoses - secondary ICD10
notes:
This field is a summary of the distinct secondary diagnoses codes a participant has had recorded across all their hospital inpatient records. Diagnoses are coded according to the International Classification of Diseases version-10 (ICD-10). There is no corresponding field available giving the first date that each code appeared in a secondary position.

If you are interested in ICD-10 diagnoses recorded as either a primary or secondary diagnosis, please see ~F41270~, and its corresponding date ~F41280~.

In order to conduct detailed analyses of the data using the source information, researchers will need to gain access to the HESIN_DIAG and HESIN tables by adding ~F41234~ and ~F41259~ to their basket.

title: Diagnoses - secondary ICD9
notes:
This field is a summary of the distinct secondary diagnoses codes a participant has had recorded across all their hospital inpatient records. Diagnoses are coded according to the International Classification of Diseases version-9 (ICD-9). There is no corresponding field giving the first date that each code appeared in a secondary position.

If you are interested in ICD-9 diagnoses recorded as either a primary or secondary diagnosis, please see ~F41271~, and its corresponding date ~F41281~.

In order to conduct detailed analyses of the data using the source information, researchers will need to gain access to the HESIN_DIAG and HESIN tables by adding ~F41234~ and ~F41259~ to their basket.

Please note ICD-9 coded hospital inpatient data are only available for older Scottish hospital records.

title: Intended management of patient (polymorphic)
notes:
This field is a summary of the distinct intended management codes a participant has had recorded in their hospital inpatient records. The intended management of a patient is their planned duration of hospital stay, i.e. whether an overnight stay was anticipated or not.

Note that the original information was obtained from a variety of external sources, some of which used overlapping and contradictory coding schemes. The values in this field can therefore only be interpreted when the source of the items is known (see ~F41253~) using the source-specific codings ~C209~ and ~C260~. It is recommended that the re-coded ~F41244~ is used instead of this one.

This field corresponds to the field INTMANAG on the HESIN table; see the Inpatient Data Dictionary (~R141140~) in ~L2000~ for information about the HESIN table.

In order to conduct detailed analyses of this data using the source information, researchers will need to gain access to the HESIN table by adding ~F41259~ to their basket.

title: Main speciality of consultant (polymorphic)
notes:
This field is a summary of the distinct consultant speciality codes a participant has had recorded in their hospital inpatient records. The main speciality of the consultant is the specialism under which the consultant is contracted, e.g. cardiology or geriatric medicine, etc.

Note that the original information was obtained from a variety of external sources, some of which used overlapping and contradictory coding schemes. The values in this field can therefore only be interpreted when the source of the items is known (see ~F41253~) using the source-specific codings ~C210~ and ~C258~. It is recommended that the re-coded ~F41245~ is used instead of this one.

This field corresponds to the field MAINSPEF on the HESIN table; see the Inpatient Data Dictionary (~R141140~) in ~L2000~ for information about the HESIN table.

In order to conduct detailed analyses of this data using the source information, researchers will need to gain access to the HESIN table by adding ~F41259~ to their basket.

title: Treatment speciality of consultant (polymorphic)
notes:
This field is a summary of the distinct treatment speciality codes a participant has had recorded in their hospital inpatient records. The treatment speciality of the consultant is the specialism under which the consultant was working, e.g. cardiology or geriatric medicine, etc.

Note that the original information was obtained from a variety of external sources, some of which used overlapping and contradictory coding schemes. The values in this field can therefore only be interpreted when the source of each item is known (see ~F41253~) using the source-specific codings ~C211~, ~C250~, ~C251~ and ~C257~. It is recommended that the re-coded ~F41246~ is used instead of this one.

This field corresponds to the field TRETSPEF on the HESIN table; see the Inpatient Data Dictionary (~R141140~) in ~L2000~ for information about the HESIN table.

In order to conduct detailed analyses of this data using the source information, researchers will need to gain access to the HESIN table by adding ~F41259~ to their basket.

title: Patient classification on admission (polymorphic)
notes:
This field is a summary of the distinct patient classification codes a participant has had recorded in their hospital inpatient records. Patient classification on admission identifies the type of patient, e.g. whether they are a regular attender or a maternity admission, etc.

Note that the original information was obtained from a variety of external sources, some of which used overlapping and contradictory coding schemes. The values in this field can therefore only be interpreted when the source of each item is known (see ~F41253~) using the source-specific codings ~C208~, ~C245~, ~C246~ and ~C254~. It is recommended that the re-coded ~F41247~ is used instead of this one.

This field corresponds to the field CLASSPAT on the HESIN table; see the Inpatient Data Dictionary (~R141140~) in ~L2000~ for information about the HESIN table.

In order to conduct detailed analyses of this data using the source information, researchers will need to gain access to the HESIN table by adding ~F41259~ to their basket.

title: Operative procedures - secondary OPCS4
notes:
This field is a summary of the secondary operation and procedure codes a participant has had recorded in their hospital inpatient records. Operative procedures are coded according to the Office of Population Censuses and Surveys Classification of Interventions and Procedures, version 4 (OPCS-4).

This field has no corresponding date field. If you are interested in operation and procedure codes (OPCS-4) recorded as either a main or secondary procedure please see ~F41272~, and its corresponding date ~F41282~.

In order to conduct detailed analyses of the data using the source information, researchers will need to gain access to the HESIN_OPER and HESIN tables by adding ~F41149~ and ~F41259~ to their basket.

title: Destinations on discharge from hospital (polymorphic)
notes:
This field is a summary of the distinct destination on discharge codes a participant has had recorded in their hospital inpatient records. Destination on discharge identifies whether a patient was due to return to their usual place of residence on leaving hospital, or whether they were due to go elsewhere.

This field corresponds to the field DISDEST on the HESIN table; see the Inpatient Data Dictionary (~R141140~) in ~L2000~ for information about the HESIN table.

notes:

Operative procedures are coded according to the Office of Population Censuses and Surveys Classification of Interventions and Procedures, version 3 (OPCS-3).

title: Operative procedures - main OPCS3
notes:

Operative procedures are coded according to the Office of Population Censuses and Surveys Classification of Interventions and Procedures, version 3 (OPCS-3).

The corresponding date when each procedure was first recorded in the inpatient data can be found in ~F41257~.

Please note OPCS-3 coded hospital inpatient data are only available for older Scottish hospital records.

title: Date of first operative procedure - main OPCS3
notes:
This field provides, for each participant, the dates when each of the main procedures in ~F41256~ was first recorded in the participant's hospital inpatient records. The date can be linked to ~F41256~ by using the array structure.

Please note that we have opted to populate this data-field with the episode start date (EPISTART in the HESIN table) or, if that was missing, the admission start date (ADMIDATE in the HESIN table) rather than use the operation date (OPDATE in the HESIN_OPER table). The rationale for this was:

  • around 1 in 5 primary procedures lacked a corresponding value for OPDATE in HESIN_OPER;

  • some recorded OPDATEs were inconsistent with the other date fields such as EPISTART, ADMIDATE, EPIEND and DISDATE (most likely due to data entry errors);

  • for those episodes with a value for OPDATE recorded the majority were the same as the value of EPISTART, with around 99% of OPDATE values within 7 days of the value of EPISTART;

  • values of EPISTART/ADMIDATE are more complete and thus may provide greater consistency across data providers.

See the Operations tab of the Hospital Inpatient Data Dictionary (~R141140~) for further information about these fields.

Please note OPCS-3 coded hospital inpatient data are only available for older Scottish hospital records.

title: Operative procedures - secondary OPCS3
notes:

This field has no corresponding date field. If you are interested in operation and procedure codes (OPCS-3) recorded as either a main or secondary procedure please see ~F41273~, and its corresponding date ~F41283~.

In order to conduct detailed analyses of the data using the source information, researchers will need to gain access to the HESIN_OPER and HESIN tables by adding ~F41149~ and ~F41259~ to their basket.

Please note OPCS-3 coded hospital inpatient data are only available for older Scottish hospital records.

title: Records in HES inpatient main dataset
notes:

If included, the field will also appear in a main UK Biobank dataset where it will give a count of the number of rows for each participant in the HESIN table.

title: Date of first operative procedure - main OPCS4
notes:
This field provides, for each participant, the dates when each of the main procedures in ~F41200~ was first recorded in the participant's hospital inpatient records. The date can be linked to ~F41200~ by using the array structure.

Please note that we have opted to populate this data-field with the episode start date (EPISTART in the HESIN table) or, if that was missing, the admission start date (ADMIDATE in the HESIN table) rather than use the operation date (OPDATE in the HESIN_OPER table). The rationale for this was:

  • around 1 in 5 primary procedures lacked a corresponding value for OPDATE in HESIN_OPER;

  • some recorded OPDATEs were inconsistent with the other date fields such as EPISTART, ADMIDATE, EPIEND and DISDATE (most likely due to data entry errors);

  • for those episodes with a value for OPDATE recorded the majority were the same as the value of EPISTART, with around 99% of OPDATE values within 7 days of the value of EPISTART;

  • values of EPISTART/ADMIDATE are more complete and thus may provide greater consistency across data providers.

See the Operations tab of the Hospital Inpatient Data Dictionary (~R141140~) for further information about these fields.

notes:

The date given is the episode start date (the EPISTART field on the HESIN table), or if this was missing the admission date (the ADMIDATE field on the HESIN table). See the Inpatient data Dictionary (~R141140~) in ~L2000~ for information about the HESIN and HESIN_DIAG tables.

The corresponding primary/main ICD10 diagnosis codes can be found in ~F41202~ and the two fields can be linked using the array structure.

title: Date of first in-patient diagnosis - main ICD9
notes:

The date given is the episode start date (the EPISTART field on the HESIN table), or if this was missing the admission date (the ADMIDATE field on the HESIN table). See the Inpatient data Dictionary (~R141140~) in ~L2000~ for information about the HESIN and HESIN_DIAG tables.

title: Records in HES inpatient delivery dataset
notes:
Adding this field to a basket will grant access to the HESIN_DELIVERY table on the Data Portal. See the Inpatient Data Dictionary (~R141140~) in ~L2000~ for information about the HESIN_DELIVERY table.

This table does not contain the date of birth of the baby (unlike the restricted HESIN_BIRTH table, see ~F41265~). Note that joining a record in HESIN_DELIVERY with the episode/admission date information in the main HESIN table will, in the vast majority of cases, provide a good approximation of the date of birth of a child.

If included, the field will also appear in a main UK Biobank dataset where it will give a count of the number of rows for each participant in the HESIN_DELIVERY table.

title: Records in HES inpatient birth dataset
notes:
Adding this field to a basket, once a project is approved to do so, will grant access to the HESIN_BIRTH table on the Data Portal.

HESIN_BIRTH is an expanded version of HESIN_DELIVERY (~F41264~) containing all of the fields from that table plus a field giving the date of birth of the child. As the date of birth field is considered sensitive, access to this table will only be given where there is special reason why access to HESIN_DELIVERY is insufficient to meet the needs of a particular research project.

Note that joining a record in HESIN_DELIVERY with the episode/admission date information in the main HESIN table will, in the vast majority of cases, provide a good approximation of the date of birth of a child.

See the Inpatient Data Dictionary (~R141140~) in ~L2000~ for further information about the HESIN_BIRTH and HESIN_DELIVERY tables.

If included, the field will also appear in a main UK Biobank dataset, where it will give a count of the number of rows for each participant in the HESIN_BIRTH table.

title: Acceleration data - cwa format
notes:
These files contain the raw acceleration data, per participant, from a single use (over a 7-day period) of the physical activity monitor. Format is native cwa as returned by the device.

Files are typically 250MB each in the raw state and usually compress to around 100MB.

title: Data problem indicator
notes: The data problem indicator was derived by combining participant reports (e.g. non-wear) with measurements of the size of the uncompressed dataset returned by the accelerometer device. This field is only present for accelerometer datasets that have had a problem recorded against them. A value of zero indicates that a dataset reported as unreliable was subsequently examined and found to be acceptable.

title: Start of requested wear period
notes: When devices were dispatched to participants they were programmed to start recording (usually at 10.00am) on a particular date, targeted to be the day they arrived at the participants address. The participant was asked to begin wearing the device immediately upon receipt. This field gives the date and time that the recording was programmed to start - which may be before or after the participant actually began wearing the device, and does not guarantee that the participant actually wore it.

title: Acceleration intensity time-series
notes:
These time-series files describe a participant's accelerometer measured physical activity intensity every five seconds. Each measurement represents the average vector magnitude across all samples recorded in each five second epoch/period. This file may be useful for those interested in analysing accelerometer measured physical activity by time.

The first column contains the acceleration value where the units of measurement are milli-gravity. The second column indicates whether this is an actual measurement (value = ) or imputed (value = 1). The time associated with each reading can be inferred from the very first row, which describes the start and end times of the data. Each successive reading is incremented by five seconds.

For example,
"acceleration (mg) - 2014-05-07 13:29:50 - 2014-05-13 09:50:25 - sampleRate = 5 seconds, imputed"
indicates that the first measurement time is at 2014-05-07 13:29:50, the second at 2014-05-07 13:29:55, the third at 2014-05-07 13:30:00 ... and the last at 2014-05-13 09:50:25.

Files are typically 760KB each in the raw state and usually compress to around 170KB.

title: Start time of wear
notes: Start time of wear

title: End time of wear
notes: End time of wear

title: Overall acceleration average
notes:
This is the recommended variable for physical activity analysis.

For final analysis of this variable, it is recommend researchers filter out participants whose data could not be calibrated (~F90016~) or who did not wear the device for sufficiently long to get a stable measure of their physical activity status (~F90015~). For a detailed description, please refer to ~R169649~.

title: Standard deviation of acceleration
notes: Standard deviation of acceleration

title: Data quality, good wear time
notes: At least three days (72 hours) of data and also having data in each one-hour period of the 24-hour cycle (scattered over multiple days)

title: Data quality, good calibration
notes:
YES indicates that the raw accelerometer data has been well calibrated.

NO indicates that a participant should be excluded from further analysis because recalibration by the preceding or subsequent measurement was not possible due to insufficient data.

title: Data quality, calibrated on own data
notes:
YES indicates sufficient data were available to conduct calibration on the participant's own stationary data (where any of the three sensor axes did not have values outside a +/- 300 milli-gravity range).

NO indicates that the data was recalibrated using the previous (or if unavailable, the next) accelerometer record from the same device worn by a different participant.

title: Daily dietary data not credible
notes:
The nutritional data was analysed to generate the daily energy intake estimate in ~F100002~. Datasets are flagged here as not being credible if the daily energy intake exceeded 20MJ for Males or 18MJ for Females.

To minimise data storage, only datasets regarded as not being plausible have been flagged.

title: Coffee consumed
notes:
Question asked: "Did you drink any coffee yesterday?"

If the participant activated the Help feature they were shown the message:

Include all coffee drinks whether hot, cold/iced, instant, shop bought (including Starbucks), machine made or made by hand. Coffee substitutes such as Barley Cup and Dandelion Coffee should not be recorded here. Instead, record this under other non-alcoholic drinks (further down the page). If some of your coffees were decaffeinated and some were not, please choose Varied for the decaf question. Likewise, if you added sugar/sweetener to some of your coffees but not all, or if the amount of sugar/sweetener you added varied from one coffee drink to another, please choose Varied. The questions on milk, decaffeinated coffee and sugar/sweetener need to be answered here.

title: Tea consumed
notes:
Question asked: "Did you drink any tea/infusion yesterday?"

If the participant activated the Help feature they were shown the message:

Standard tea covers all the different types of tea made with black tea leaves (this is the most common type of tea). This includes teabags and loose leaf tea as well as decaffeinated types. Peppermint tea belongs in the herbal or fruit infusion section. If you added honey to your tea/infusion, please treat this as sugar. Do not treat artificial sweetener as sugar. If your tea or infusion is not on the list, please record it under Other located at the bottom of the list.

notes:
Question asked: "Did you have any alcoholic drinks yesterday? For instance, beer, wine or spirits."

If the participant activated the Help feature they were shown the message:

Please treat liqueurs as spirits. If you had mixed drinks such as shandy, cocktails or alcopops, think about what went in them. For example, shandy is made from beer, lager or cider (please record the lemonade or ginger beer used in the shandy separately); cocktails and alcopops contain one or more spirits. Alcohol used in cooking should be ignored.

For example: if the soup being served in a cafe has a brand name such as Heinz, please choose carton/pouch/canned soup; if the soup has been freshly prepared in a restaurant, please choose home-made soup. title: Vegetable consumers
notes:
Question asked: "Did you eat any beans, lentils, potatoes or vegetables yesterday? Include fresh, tinned, frozen, dried; chips, salad, coleslaw, baked beans, chickpeas, veg in stews, pies etc."

If the participant activated the Help feature they were shown the message:

Please include all vegetables, whether they are eaten by themselves, as an accompaniment or within a particular dish/meal such as a stew or pie. A serving of vegetables would be the typical amount dished up as an accompaniment to main meal. e.g. if you had a roast dinner with meat, potatoes, carrots and peas, most people would have one serving of potatoes, one serving of carrots and one serving of peas. For small amounts of vegetables that are not big enough to be counted individually (e.g. in a stew), please guess the number of servings and record that under Vegetable pieces. A serving is about the amount that would be dished up using a serving spoon (large spoon typically used in canteens or self-service buffets). Example: a beef stew with carrot and parsnip may have enough vegetables in it to count as a half serving of carrots plus a half serving of parsnip (possibly even a whole serving if there are a lot of vegetables in the stew). If not, it may be better to record the vegetables as a half serving of Vegetable pieces. For a selection of vegetables where the precise type may be unknown (for example in a shop bought vegetable pie or a stir fry cooked by a friend) please guess the total amount and record that under Vegetable pieces. Olives should have been recorded earlier under 'Savoury Snacks'. If your vegetable is not on the list, please record it under 'Other' located at the bottom of the list.

title: Fruit consumers
notes:
Question asked: "Did you eat any fruit yesterday?"

If the participant activated the Help feature they were shown the message:

Include fresh, frozen, dried, canned or cooked. Help section: Please include all fruit, whether eaten by itself or as part of a sweet or savoury dish (e.g. fruit pie or crumble; pork cooked with apple). Fruits recorded under cooked & dried should not be recorded individually further down the list. Small amounts of fruit that are not big enough to be counted individually, or where the precise type may be unknown (e.g. in a mixed fruit salad), please guess the total amount and record that under Mixed fruit. As canned fruit usually comes in segments or slices, please give your answer in servings rather than as whole fruit. Fruit used in a smoothie should not be recorded here. The fruit smoothie should have been recorded in the drinks section. Chocolate covered fruit (e.g. chocolate raisins) and yogurt covered fruit (e.g. yogurt coated pineapple) should not be recorded here. Instead record it under sweet snacks (several pages earlier). Dried fruit that is included with cereals such as Sultana Bran and Optivita should not be record here because it should have been recorded on the cereals page. If your fruit is not on the list, please record it under Other located at the bottom of the list.

title: Time spent doing vigorous physical activity
notes:
Question asked: "Yesterday, about how long did you spend doing activities that needed vigorous effort, making you breathe hard? For example running, cycling uphill, carrying heavy furniture upstairs, martial arts, competitive sports or intensive exercise."

If the participant activated the Help feature they were shown the message:

Please guess how long you spent in total doing activities requiring vigorous effort yesterday. These types of strenuous activities require a good level of fitness and strength. At work: physically demanding such as carrying heavy objects (e.g. bricks) or carrying moderately heavy objects uphill, up stairs or up ladders, heavy shovelling etc. Running: not slow - 5mph (1 mile in 12 minutes) or faster. Cycling: vigorous effort, reasonably fast or uphill, mountain biking. Sports/exercise: vigorous effort including step aerobics, intensive circuit training, boxing/martial arts, competitively played team games such as football, rock climbing, energetic swimming, energetic skiing (racing, cross-country) etc.

title: Time spent doing moderate physical activity
notes:
Question asked: "Yesterday, about how long did you spend doing activities that needed moderate effort, making you somewhat short of breath? For example walking upstairs, going to the gym, jogging, energetic dancing, aerobics, most sports, using heavy power tools and other physically demanding DIY & gardening."

If the participant activated the Help feature they were shown the message:

Please guess how long you spent in total doing medium effort activities yesterday. How tired you feel from these types of activities will depend on your individual level of fitness (so a fitter person will not need to breathe as hard as a less fit person). At work: carrying moderately heavy objects, pushing a wheelchair, using heavy power tools, active farm work, taking care of farm animals, coal mining, teaching sports etc. Walking: very brisk walking or walking uphill, walking upstairs, backpacking, marching, power walking, using crutches etc. Jogging: this is defined as running at a gentle pace. Dancing: fast or energetic dancing (not slow ballroom dancing). Cycling: for travelling to work or leisure (not racing or uphill) cycling, also includes unicycling. Sports/exercise: push-ups, weight-lifting, working out in a gym, aerobics, team sports (not competitively played) such as football, golf, horse riding, tennis, track & field, gentle swimming, skiing, ice-skating etc. Gardening: includes energetic tasks such as digging, light to moderate shovelling, mowing the lawn, using heavy power tools, chopping wood etc. DIY/home improvement: includes such fairly demanding tasks such as building a fence, sawing hardwood, cleaning gutters, using heavy power tools, sanding floors etc.

title: Time spent doing light physical activity
notes:
Question asked: "Yesterday, about how long did you spend doing activities that needed some light effort, involving movement but not making you short of breath? For example shopping, cooking, housework, playing darts/pool/bowls, walking, light exercise like stretching, gentle dancing, caring for people/animals, decorating, light gardening, playing musical instruments."

If the participant activated the Help feature they were shown the message:

Please guess how long you spent in total doing activities requiring relatively little physical effort yesterday. These types of activities should not get you out of breath (or only a little out of breath) but can make you tired if carried out for a long time. Walking: should not get you out of breath, includes walking whilst carrying a child or pushing a buggy, walking about the home, walking about the office, walking for pleasure etc. At work: light carpentry, making beds, cleaning, electrical work, plumbing, painting/decorating, light farming tasks such as harvesting, rounding up cattle/animals, locksmith, machine/equipment operator, assembling/repairing, directing traffic, teaching yoga, bartending, nursing, tailoring, theatre work (acting, working backstage) etc. Housework: includes both light and heavy housework such as cleaning, scrubbing, washing, hanging the washing to dry, vacuuming, ironing, cooking, feeding pets, putting away the shopping, making beds etc. Shopping: food and non-food shopping. Playing musical instruments: playing instruments whilst seated or standing (i.e. not in a marching band). Also includes conducting. Caring: children, sick, elderly, animals. Gardening: watering the plants/lawn, weeding, using a ride-on lawn mower, picking fruit/flowers etc. DIY/home improvement: general carpentry, decorating (painting, putting up wallpaper, plastering, scraping), car repairs, wiring, plumbing etc. Games: darts, snooker/pool, bowling, bowls, croquet, frisbee (gentle/moderate), playing catch, mini golf etc. Dancing: slow dancing that does not get you out of breath. Sports/exercise: activities that should not get you out of breath such as stretching, hatha yoga, horse riding (at walking pace), sailing (not competitive), using power boats etc.

title: When diet questionnaire completed
notes: This field holds the time at which participants completed the questionnaire by pressing the Confirm button.

title: When diet questionnaire started
notes: This field holds the time at which participants started the questionnaire as indicated by beginning the first page.

title: Invitation to complete online 24-hour recall dietary questionnaire, acceptance
notes: Response to emailed invitation to complete online 24-hour recall dietary questionnaire. There is no data for instance=0 since this was completed as part of the initial assessment centre.

title: Invitation to complete online 24-hour recall dietary questionnaire, date sent
notes:
Dates that invitations to complete online 24-hour recall dietary questionnaire were emailed to participants. Following an initial ramp-up phase approximately 6000 invitations were emailed each day. The response rate was typically 30-35%.

During initial part of the first run of the questionnaire, information was not recorded on participants who did not respond, so the response rate will appear to be 100% for that early period.

title: Invitation to assessment centre, acceptance
notes:
Responses to invitation to assessment centre.

During the 2012-13 repeat assessment (instance 1), participants who attended without invitation were often the family member or friend of a participant who did receive an invitation. Those participants who accepted without attending, booked an appointment and then failed to attend. More information on this assessment visit can be found here: ~Xrepeat_assessment_2012~Repeat assessment (2012-13)~

title: Invitation to physical activity study, acceptance
notes: Response to invitation to physical activity study using accelerometer.

title: Invitation to physical activity study, date sent
notes: Date of invitation to physical activity study. The rate of sending email invitations was varied dynamically to achieve a target throughput of 200 devices per day.

title: Newsletter communications, date sent
notes: Newsletters are sent to participants at periodic intervals. This field records the date of dispatch of such communications - note that dispatch does not imply either successful receipt or that a recipient actually read the material sent.

title: Invitation to assessment centre, date sent

title: EMBARGOED UNLINKED : DXA images
notes:
EMBARGOED UNLINKED re-imaging for Calico/CZI

Contains the DXA image set as generated by the scanning device.
Includes whole body; lateral thoraco-lumbar spine; right and left hips; right and left knees .

title: EMBARGOED UNLINKED : Dixon technique for internal fat - DICOM
notes:
EMBARGOED UNLINKED re-imaging for Calico/CZI

Dixon technique. Measures internal fat. Neck-to-knee images.

title: EMBARGOED UNLINKED : Pancreatic fat - DICOM
notes:
EMBARGOED UNLINKED re-imaging for Calico/CZI

Measures fat in and around pancreas.

title: EMBARGOED UNLINKED : Liver imaging - gradient echo - DICOM
notes:
EMBARGOED UNLINKED re-imaging for Calico/CZI

Liver images collected using gradient echo. This protocol was superceded during 2016 by ~F20254~.

title: EMBARGOED UNLINKED : Liver Imaging - T1 ShMoLLI - DICOM
notes:
EMBARGOED UNLINKED re-imaging for Calico/CZI

Experimental sequence developed by Oxford OCMR group. A single breath-hold cardiac-gated T1-mapping Modified Look-Locker Inversion Recovery sequence (typically 12 seconds), which acquires a series of seven images (8mm slice thickness, in-plane pixel spacing 9.3mm) each with a different T1 weighting.

title: EMBARGOED UNLINKED : Measurements of pancreas volume - DICOM
notes:
EMBARGOED UNLINKED re-imaging for Calico/CZI

Different method of measuring fat around pancreas (one will likely be dropped eventually).

title: EMBARGOED UNLINKED : Scout images for heart MRI - DICOM
notes:
EMBARGOED UNLINKED re-imaging for Calico/CZI

Scout images for heart scans

title: EMBARGOED UNLINKED : Long axis heart images - DICOM
notes:
EMBARGOED UNLINKED re-imaging for Calico/CZI

Long Axis measures in three directions to cover various chambers of the heart.

title: EMBARGOED UNLINKED : Short axis heart images - DICOM
notes:
EMBARGOED UNLINKED re-imaging for Calico/CZI

Short axis scans. Used to measure function of heart.

Note that the number will vary depending on the size of the participant since the larger the heart the more slices are required. There should always be a relationship between the number of images in the _inlineVF series and the number of SAX series. Roughly invlineVF = SAX_b1 + b2 + bn + LAX_2ch _ LAX_3ch + LAX_4ch.

title: EMBARGOED UNLINKED : Aortic distensibilty images - DICOM
notes:
EMBARGOED UNLINKED re-imaging for Calico/CZI

Aortic distensibilty scans.

title: EMBARGOED UNLINKED : Cine tagging images - DICOM
notes:
EMBARGOED UNLINKED re-imaging for Calico/CZI

Cine tagging

title: EMBARGOED UNLINKED : Left ventricular outflow tract images - DICOM
notes:
EMBARGOED UNLINKED re-imaging for Calico/CZI

Left Ventricular Outflow Tract scan.

title: EMBARGOED UNLINKED : Blood flow images - DICOM
notes:
EMBARGOED UNLINKED re-imaging for Calico/CZI

Measures blood flow to try and identify heart disease.

title: EMBARGOED UNLINKED : Experimental shMOLLI sequence images - DICOM
notes:
EMBARGOED UNLINKED re-imaging for Calico/CZI

Experimental shMOLLI sequence used by Oxford OCMR.

title: EMBARGOED UNLINKED : Scout images for brain scans - DICOM
notes:
EMBARGOED UNLINKED re-imaging for Calico/CZI

Scout images for brain scans

title: EMBARGOED UNLINKED : T1 structural brain images - DICOM
notes:
EMBARGOED UNLINKED re-imaging for Calico/CZI

The DICOM image was acquired using the following parameters:

Resolution: 1x1x1 mm
Field-of-view: 208x256x256 matrix
Scan duration: 5 minutes
3D MPRAGE, sagittal, in-plane acceleration iPAT=2, prescan-normalise

title: EMBARGOED UNLINKED : Functional brain images - task - DICOM
notes:
EMBARGOED UNLINKED re-imaging for Calico/CZI

The DICOM images were acquired using the following parameters:

Resolution: 2.4x2.4x2.4 mm
Field-of-view: 88x88x64 matrix
Duration: 4 minutes (332 timepoints)
TR: 0.735 s
TE: 39ms
GE-EPI with x8 multislice acceleration, no iPAT, flip angle 52 degrees, fat saturation

As implemented in the CMRR multiband acquisition, a separate "single-band reference scan" is also acquired. title: EMBARGOED UNLINKED : Arterial spin labelling brain images - NIFTI
notes:
EMBARGOED UNLINKED re-imaging for Calico/CZI

Arterial Spin Labelling images in NIFTI format. The source DICOM image was acquired using the following parameters:

  • Resolution: 3.4x3.4x4.5 mm
  • Field-of-view: 64x48x32 matrix
  • Scan duration: 2 minutes
  • Preparation: Multi-postlabelling delay pseudocontinuous arterial spin labelling, labelling duration 1800 ms, postlabelling delays 400, 800, 1200, 1600 and 2000 ms, labelling plane offset from the centre of the imaging volume 90 mm
  • Readout: 2-shot segmented 3D-GRASE, left-right phase encoding, refocussing flip angle 120
  • Background suppression: pre-saturation and two inversion pulses (to null tissues with T1 = 700 ms and 1400 ms, 100 ms prior to excitation)
  • Volumes: one label/control pair per postlabelling delay plus one calibration (M0) volume without labelling or background suppression (effective TR 5000 ms).
The average size of these NIFTI datasets is 75MB per participant.

title: EMBARGOED UNLINKED : Quantitative susceptibility mapping images - NIFTI
notes:
EMBARGOED UNLINKED re-imaging for Calico/CZI

Quantitative susceptibility mapping images (derived from swMRI data) in NIFTI format. The source swMRI DICOM image was acquired using the following parameters:

  • Resolution: 0.8x0.8x3 mm
  • Field-of-view: 256x288x48 matrix
  • Duration: 2.5 minutes
  • Two echos, TE=9.42,20 ms
  • 3D, axial, in-plane acceleration iPAT=2, partial Fourier = 7/8, prescan-normalise
The average size of these NIFTI datasets is 25 MB per participant.

2D, axial, in-plane acceleration iPAT=2, partial Fourier = 7/8, prescan-normalise

To date (Oct 2015) the magnitude and phase images have been saved for each RF coil and echo time separately. In future the expectation is to combine these on the scanner.

The average size of these NIFTI datasets is 35MB per participant.

title: EMBARGOED LINKED : Arterial spin labelling brain images - NIFTI
notes:
EMBARGOED LINKED re-imaging for Calico/CZI

Arterial Spin Labelling images in NIFTI format. The source DICOM image was acquired using the following parameters:

  • Resolution: 3.4x3.4x4.5 mm
  • Field-of-view: 64x48x32 matrix
  • Scan duration: 2 minutes
  • Preparation: Multi-postlabelling delay pseudocontinuous arterial spin labelling, labelling duration 1800 ms, postlabelling delays 400, 800, 1200, 1600 and 2000 ms, labelling plane offset from the centre of the imaging volume 90 mm
  • Readout: 2-shot segmented 3D-GRASE, left-right phase encoding, refocussing flip angle 120
  • Background suppression: pre-saturation and two inversion pulses (to null tissues with T1 = 700 ms and 1400 ms, 100 ms prior to excitation)
  • Volumes: one label/control pair per postlabelling delay plus one calibration (M0) volume without labelling or background suppression (effective TR 5000 ms).
The average size of these NIFTI datasets is 75MB per participant.

title: EMBARGOED LINKED : Quantitative susceptibility mapping images - NIFTI
